/* Per-post Claude prompt archive: the human prompts that built each post, shown in
   the About-page tile tray. Extracted from this machine's Claude Code session transcripts
   (sessions that edited the post's files), then hand-cleaned for typos/profanity/public
   safety while keeping the instructions faithful (they get re-run against future models).
   Source of truth: research/prompts/<slug>.json. Rebuild: node tools/build-post-prompts.mjs --bundle */
window.POST_PROMPTS = {"the-other-side":{"title":"The Other Side","href":"the-other-side.html","count":7,"prompts":[{"when":"2026-07-02T00:07","text":"Okay, so I want to just focus on the words to use for a blog post right now; I can make the blog post next. Below I have my rough draft theory I want to present. For every single aspect that is already referencing real established things I want a beautiful way of referencing it, then the parts that are mine, we don't reference anything. I think the concept that there exists an equal attraction on the other side, and that the two are actually equivalent in value, and moving close to the middle or far away also exists on both sides. The golden ratio spiral isn't too important, just a fun way to visualize, but the fact that the slope can only get infinitely closer is important. Also please check out voice.md for writing this.\n\nWhen you do DMT, you experience the other side, described in the Tao Te Ching. You haven't crossed over, but you move to be more close to it. The other side is equally as interested in their 'other side' as we are of the 'nothing' side. I am being careful to not give pronouns or anything to the other side, because if a word is used, that's not the other side. The more complex a being is on our side, or more special/unique, the further it gets from the other side and the more myriad it becomes. Therefore rocks are far more 'spiritually fit' if you will (AKA understanding that there is no me or you or yellow or green, the other side's understanding) than animals, and animals are typically more spiritually fit than humans because they are closer to the other side, because of reduction of 'self,' which is a separator, a unifier, pushing us deeper into the myriad world. I'm not saying rocks are perfectly in line; they still have gravity and atomic effects on them so they're not entirely spiritually fit either, they are on our side, but they're just closer.\n\nDeath and DMT are very similar and very different at the exact same time. Death brings you to the other side, but not 'you,' and if you 'bring something back' what really happened was you got close, not crossed over, because if 'you' were there, you weren't on the other side. There does not exist a you, or any you, on that side. DMT shuts off a very specific part of the brain which is like the ego, quickly reducing 'self' and rocketing us closer to the other side, but we still have auditory, all of our sensory and emotions. So when we think we 'visit,' we're really just moving closer temporarily. We're still on our side. We're just a lot closer to the middle. The other side is not a better place or a worse place or a right place or the wrong place, as a matter of fact. A cup is useless without the empty space within it, and the empty space is useless without a thing to contrast it. Neither the nothing world nor the myriad world are better or right or wrong. They simply exist together.\n\nCrossover cannot actually happen because if you went to the other side, you couldn't have a brain. So when the two sides come together, it's like an infinite exponential thing, kind of like when you try to reach the speed of light where you get exponentially closer and closer, but you can never cross. The Tao says that the only mystery in existence is one side looking at the other. And to be clear, there are not beings on the other side; the word 'being' quite literally implies you're on the myriad side. Lastly, one side only exists and can only exist with the other. They are equally as important. But there is an attraction that both sides feel, the ultimate mystery; this mystery is the only requirement for the existence of both sides. Each side is like a golden ratio spiral where they come together at the widest radius, never quite touching, like a speed of light curve, and then as you go away from the joining point you spin in, and eventually, on the myriad side of things, what this looks like is as big of an ego as you can get: money, power, things, or like a cocaine addict who really wants cocaine. Desire can lead you far that way, nothing but things, like not thinking of others and what you can do for them, not thinking of anything else, thinking only of yourself. And then there is an equivalent of this on the other side (again, there are not beings on that side, but there is an equivalent of getting further and further away from the myriad world). There is also an equivalent of attraction to the other side, on the other side."},{"when":"2026-07-02T00:35","text":"Now I want a blog post, but only local."},{"when":"2026-07-02T00:37","text":"The focus should not be anywhere near DMT. That's just a point about how hallucinogens turn off the 'self' part of the brain."},{"when":"2026-07-02T00:50","text":"The visual is supposed to be two golden spirals, but they should be positioned to truly show that when they come up on the dotted line they have that same mathematical curve that coming up on the speed of light has, where it always gets closer but never touches."},{"when":"2026-07-02T01:38","text":"So I don't think the opening works, because the Tao says that the nameless side created the named side. I don't claim that I know how creation works, although this is addressed in the audit section (some people may not read that far). Also I think we need to make bold 'The book opens with the same warning.' Also the link styling here does not match my others, where I keep all 81 chapters side by side.\n\nI also think people may leave after reading this section: 'The other side gets no pronouns in this post,' because it's a little too floaty and woo. I think the post deserves to be taken seriously, but still, I should not be held back by meeting others' standards of normal.\n\nIn the audit section, 'clay wrapped around a hollow' is too hard to understand; my readers may not know what a hollow is, same with the reference to 30 spokes. My readers may be like 'what?'\n\nAlso, is it really true that 'they are the two halves of one cup. That claim is mine.'? Like... is my thought truly original?\n\nHere I think we can italicize the word saying 'By my own rule nobody can, because saying is a this-side activity.' Where else maybe should we do this?\n\nFor the quotes, I think I should use a component I already built; I don't like this new one you made.\n\nIn this sentence, I don't understand, and my readers won't understand, 'notice the tradition got there.' I just don't get what that means: 'If ranking people below gravel sounds like an insult, notice the tradition got there first.'\n\nFor the visual, I actually want it flipped upside down so they come close at the bottom, not the top. Also we need to label both sides more simply, and need to show an arrow showing an increase in self or something like that, okay? So let's get this visual setup right. Also, way too many words to describe the visual below!\n\nI think when we say 'lean point' that is confusing; it's not language people are used to. Need an alternative.\n\nCan we make all this like a drop-down box? 'The theory is mine and carries no authority. The furniture it stands on is real and checkable, and every quotation above is verbatim from a named translator. The Tao Te Ching quotes: chapters 1, 2, 11, 32, 40, and 56, in the translations named inline (Feng and English 1972, Waley 1934, Bynner 1944, Legge 1891, with Lau 1963 for \"the myriad creatures\"), all side by side in the site's Tao Te Ching explorer. The census word: wanwu is literally \"ten thousand things\"; English myriad comes from the Greek myrias, ten thousand. Zhuangzi's downhill list: Zhuangzi chapter 22, in Burton Watson's translation. Hallucinogens and the self network: Carhart-Harris et al., PNAS 2012. Meditation and the same network: Brewer et al., PNAS 2011. The death rhyme: Timmermann et al., Frontiers in Psychology 2018. The proton gap: CERN, the LHC reaches 0.999999990 times the speed of light, about seven miles per hour short. Nothing here is advice, medical or otherwise.'\n\nThis part I disagree with: 'Distance from the middle is self, on both sides, out to a far end where a self is nothing but self.' I don't claim self is the distance on the other side; I don't know what makes the distance on that side. Also 'Two sides, exactly equal: neither prior, neither better, neither a place.' I disagree with this too: our side does have actual places, but the other side doesn't??\n\nAlso, why is this at the end? What does this mean? 'Past that, no pronouns, no verbs, and no post.'"},{"when":"2026-07-02T11:39","text":"How can we incorporate that there is no physical distance between the two? Only a myriad creature would even assume that, and I realized that's who's reading this!"},{"when":"2026-07-02T11:51","text":"Great, now include it in my Inner Life collection, get a nice artist's depiction of a black hole as the thumbnail (don't care about copyright), and push to prod."}]},"art-of-war":{"title":"The Art of War, Side by Side","href":"art-of-war.html","count":1,"prompts":[{"when":"2026-06-20T17:00","text":"You're building the Art of War post for my great-books series. Engine A, the translation stack (short and aphoristic, near-ideal for it).\n\nRULES: First read CANON.md (especially \"What the first posts taught us\" and \"The map\"), then VOICE.md and STYLE.md, study tao-te-ching.html with js/tao*.js, clone that architecture. Follow the rules: voice is the bar (write-post plus monotone test, plain spoken, never formal); open concrete; source the translations yourself via sub-agents, never ask me; 20px gutter at 375px; real sourced thumbnail (named); homepage card description ONE short hook line of about 15 words.\n\nSpine: the supreme skill is to win without fighting; war is deception; shape the situation so the outcome is decided before the first blow, and know both yourself and your enemy.\n\nKeystones: \"the supreme art of war is to subdue the enemy without fighting\"; \"all warfare is based on deception\"; \"know the enemy and know yourself, and in a hundred battles you will never be in peril\"; be formless like water, adapting to the ground; win first, then seek the battle; the use of terrain and spies.\n\nSplits to stack: shi (strategic configuration, momentum, latent force, famously hard to render), plus the words for deception and formlessness. Chinese source line.\n\nTranslations (all fair game, name each): Lionel Giles (1910 public domain), Samuel Griffith, Thomas Cleary, John Minford, the Denma group, Roger Ames, Victor Mair. It is applied everywhere now (business, sport), but root it in its real context first, then let the reader draw the modern lines.\n\nShip: card (ONE short hook line), og:image, real sourced thumbnail (named), 20px gutter at 375px, write-post self-edit, commit and push with explicit paths."}]},"camus":{"title":"The Myth of Sisyphus","href":"camus.html","count":1,"prompts":[{"when":"2026-06-21T01:16","text":"You're building the Camus \"Myth of Sisyphus\" post for my great-books series. Engine C, idea distillation. It belongs in the philosophy hub.\n\nRULES: First read CANON.md (especially \"What the first posts taught us\"), then VOICE.md and STYLE.md, study tao-te-ching.html for the shell. Voice is the bar (write-post skill plus the monotone read-aloud test, plain and spoken, never formal); open concrete with an everyday analogy; source the book and translations yourself via sub-agents, never ask me; 20px gutter at 375px; real sourced thumbnail (named).\n\nSpine: \"There is but one truly serious philosophical problem, and that is suicide.\" If the universe has no built-in meaning, the clash between our hunger for it and the silence is the absurd. Camus says do not escape the absurd, by suicide or by a leap of faith, but revolt against it and live fully without appeal.\n\nKeystones: the absurd (the divorce between us and a silent world); the three responses (suicide is physical escape, faith is \"philosophical suicide,\" revolt is honest); living without appeal; \"one must imagine Sisyphus happy.\"\n\nEngine C: distill. 1942. Set it deliberately against the live Frankl post: Frankl finds a meaning in suffering, Camus denies built-in meaning and affirms life anyway. That argument is the post.\n\nSHIP: add it to its hub, not a homepage card. In tools/gen-hubs.mjs flip the \"Camus, The Myth of Sisyphus\" coming-soon line in the philosophy hub to a live entry (href, title, thumb filename, a short one-line description ~15 to 20 words), then run `node tools/gen-hubs.mjs` and `node tools/build-search-index.mjs`. Add the og:image block, verify the 20px gutter at 375px, commit and push to main with explicit paths."}]},"case-for-god":{"title":"Can You Argue Your Way to God?","href":"case-for-god.html","count":1,"prompts":[{"when":"2026-06-21T03:37","text":"Build one new post for my site (a static HTML/CSS/JS site, GitHub Pages). It is part\nof my \"great books, made learn-from-able\" canon series. This post pairs the two most\nfamous arguments that you should believe in God: C.S. Lewis's Mere Christianity (1952)\nand Pascal's Wager from the Pensées (c. 1660). One post, one spine, not two glued halves.\n\nFIRST, read these and follow them exactly:\n- VOICE.md (the calibrated house voice; apply the monotone-read-aloud test, the BLUF\n  openers, and the LLM-tell kill-list). Use the write-post skill if present.\n- CANON.md (the series brief and the four engines). This post is ENGINE C: idea\n  distillation, the same model as the Viktor Frankl post (frankl.html). Read frankl.html\n  to match the format and depth.\n- HARD RULES: no em dashes anywhere (use commas, periods, parentheses, or \"to\").\n  Open concrete, with an everyday analogy or scene, NOT an abstract thesis. Define every\n  term in line. Imperial units if any come up.\n\nTHE SPINE (this is the whole point of the post): these are the two best-known reasoned\ncases for faith, and they are both brilliant AND both have famous holes. Build each\nargument at full strength (steelman it so a believer nods), then keep the strongest\nobjection visibly in the room. Do not resolve it into a tidy \"and so God is real\" or a\nsmug \"and so it's all nonsense.\" This matches my truth-over-narrative rule: being right\nbeats being reassuring. A reader should come away understanding the arguments better than\nmost believers and most atheists do.\n\nTHE SUBSTANCE (verify every quote and citation yourself; name and locate each one):\n\n1) PASCAL'S WAGER (Pensees, fragment Lafuma 418 / Brunschvicg 233, \"Infini-rien\").\n   Steelman: reason cannot settle whether God exists, but you are already in the game and\n   must bet with how you live. Bet on God and he exists: infinite gain. Bet on God and he\n   doesn't: you lose almost nothing. So the rational wager is God. Note Pascal basically\n   invented expected-value decision theory to make this point. Include his own answer to\n   \"but I can't just choose to believe\": act as if you do (the habits, the holy water) and\n   belief will follow.\n   Best objections to keep in: the many-gods problem (which God? one who punishes belief?);\n   you can't believe on command (though Pascal pre-answers); a real God might despise\n   mercenary belief; the infinity math breaks normal decision theory. The honest read: it\n   is not evidence God exists, it's an argument about betting under uncertainty.\n\n2) LEWIS, MERE CHRISTIANITY (1952, from his 1941-44 BBC wartime talks).\n   a) The Moral Argument (Book I, \"Right and Wrong as a Clue to the Meaning of the\n      Universe\"): everyone appeals to a standard of fair play they expect others to know;\n      Lewis argues this Moral Law is not herd instinct or mere convention, and points to\n      something mind-like behind the universe.\n      Best objection: evolutionary and social accounts of conscience, the is/ought gap, and\n      that even a real moral law doesn't get you to a personal or Christian God.\n   b) The Trilemma (Book II, \"What Christians Believe,\" the \"Liar, Lunatic, or Lord\"\n      passage, \"...on a level with the man who says he is a poached egg\"): Jesus claimed to\n      be God, so you cannot call him merely a great moral teacher; he is a liar, a lunatic,\n      or Lord.\n      Best objection, and this is the key honest beat: it is a FALSE trilemma. It omits\n      \"Legend\" (the Gospels may not accurately report that he claimed divinity, which many\n      scholars hold) and \"sincerely mistaken but sane.\" Lewis's unstated load-bearing\n      premise is that the Gospel reports are accurate. Most philosophers treat the trilemma\n      as the weakest of his arguments for exactly this reason. Say so plainly.\n   Also explain \"mere\" Christianity: the common core all denominations share (his image of\n   a hall with rooms off it).\n\nTHE HONEST CLOSE: what these arguments actually do. They are not skeptic-converting proofs.\nThey are closer to (a) reasons it can be rational to bet, and (b) articulations that make\nfaith intellectually respectable for someone already drawn to it. Both have holes. But both\nland something true: Pascal, that you wager with your life whether you like it or not;\nLewis, that \"just a great moral teacher\" dodges what the texts actually claim. Leave both\nthe force and the holes standing.\n\nSUGGESTED STRUCTURE: concrete opener (someone asked to actually justify a belief, or a\nplain bet/coin image) -> Pascal the gambler-mathematician and his bet -> the cracks in the\nbet -> Lewis on the radio and his two moves -> the crack in the trilemma (the missing\n\"legend\") -> the honest close. Short chapter-pill strip if it fits frankl.html's format.\n\nTITLE: follow my title rule. Brainstorm broadly, pick a title that describes the content\ndirectly (no provenance conceits), then set it IDENTICAL across the hub card, <title>,\nog:title, and <h1>. Working title to beat: \"Can You Argue Your Way to God?\". Suggested\nslug: case-for-god.html.\n\nTHUMBNAIL: source a REAL image (never generative, never ask me to fetch it, find it\nyourself). A public-domain portrait of Pascal or Lewis works, or an image that reads as a\nbet/argument. Make assets/thumbs/<slug>.jpg AND a .webp sibling\n(cwebp -q 82 assets/thumbs/<slug>.jpg -o assets/thumbs/<slug>.webp), plus an og:image.\n\nPLACEMENT (this is the part people get wrong now, read it carefully): do NOT add a homepage\ncard. The series lives in four hub index pages. Add this post as a member of the HUBS array\nin tools/gen-hubs.mjs, in the 'philosophy' hub (it is philosophy of religion and pairs as\nthe direct counterpoint to the Nietzsche post; if you think it fits 'inner-life' better,\nnext to William James, that's a defensible alternative, ask me). The live() helper takes\nSIX args: live(href, title, thumb, era, year, desc). Use era '1660 & 1952' and year 1952.\nThen run, in order: node tools/gen-hubs.mjs, then\nnode tools/wrap-picture.mjs religion.html philosophy.html inner-life.html\npower-story-love.html index.html (gen-hubs emits bare <img>; wrap-picture restores the WebP\n<picture> wrapping it would otherwise strip), then node tools/build-search-index.mjs.\nCommit your new files plus philosophy.html, index.html, search-index.json, gen-hubs.mjs.\n\nWORKFLOW: origin/main is very hot (many parallel sessions). Work in a worktree off\norigin/main, commit, and push HEAD:main; if rejected, rebase or rebuild on the new base.\nA git pre-commit hook blocks em dashes and LLM tells. Commit and push when done; Pages\nauto-deploys."}]},"cults-business":{"title":"When a Path Becomes a Business","href":"cults-business.html","count":1,"prompts":[{"when":"2026-06-21T01:18","text":"You're building the second cults post for my great-books series, \"how a path becomes a business.\" Engine D, a clearly labeled case study, not an endorsement. It belongs in the inner-life hub.\n\nRULES: First read CANON.md (especially \"What the first posts taught us,\" \"Four approaches,\" and the gate), then VOICE.md and STYLE.md, study tao-te-ching.html for the shell. Voice is the bar (write-post plus monotone test, plain spoken, never formal); open concrete; source the material yourself via sub-agents, never ask me; 20px gutter at 375px; real sourced thumbnail (named).\n\nSpine: the other failure mode is not the cage but the cash register. How spirituality gets monetized, and where teaching ends and selling begins.\n\nCover: the Large Group Awareness Trainings (est and Werner Erhard, the Landmark Forum, the weekend that breaks you down and sells you the next level); A Course in Miracles (the channeled \"scripture\" and its industry); the prosperity gospel (name it and claim it, the private-jet pastors); the wellness-industrial complex and multi-level marketing as religion; and Maharishi's TM empire (the thousands of dollars, the \"yogic flying\" upsell).\n\nEngine D, case study. The honest question: is charging for enlightenment inherently corrupt, or just the cost of the lights? Steelman before you judge.\n\nSHIP: add it to its hub, not a homepage card. In tools/gen-hubs.mjs make the second cults line in the inner-life hub (the business one, from splitting the combined entry) a live entry (href, title, thumb, ~15-20 word description), then run `node tools/gen-hubs.mjs` and `node tools/build-search-index.mjs`. Add the og:image, verify the 20px gutter at 375px, commit and push with explicit paths."}]},"darwin":{"title":"Darwin and the Watchmaker","href":"darwin.html","count":1,"prompts":[{"when":"2026-06-20T16:59","text":"You're building the Darwin post for my great-books series. Engine B, walk his actual argument.\n\nRULES: First read CANON.md (especially \"What the first posts taught us\" and \"The map\"), then VOICE.md and STYLE.md, study tao-te-ching.html for the shell. Follow the rules: voice is the bar (write-post plus monotone test, plain spoken, never formal or \"educational,\" and this one is at high risk of going lecture-mode, do not let it); open concrete with an everyday analogy; source the editions and the scholarship yourself via sub-agents, never ask me; 20px gutter at 375px; real sourced thumbnail (named); homepage card description ONE short hook line of about 15 words.\n\nSpine: the staggering design and variety of living things looks like it must have a designer; Darwin shows it needs none, only descent with modification under natural selection, given enough time.\n\nKeystones: artificial selection (pigeon breeders) as the on-ramp; the struggle for existence; natural selection; descent with modification; the single diagram in the whole book, the tree of life; the hard cases he faces head-on (the eye); deep time; the closing line, \"endless forms most beautiful.\"\n\nSpecial: precision matters, his readers are exacting. Work from the first edition (1859), which has the cleanest argument before later editions hedged. Do not conflate him with social Darwinism or treat \"survival of the fittest\" as a moral claim (that phrase is Spencer's, not Darwin's ethics). Use concrete analogies throughout (breeders shaping pigeons over generations, a slow river carving a canyon). Quote any good modern edition's apparatus with attribution.\n\nShip: card (ONE short hook line), og:image, real sourced thumbnail (named), 20px gutter at 375px, write-post self-edit, commit and push with explicit paths."}]},"fox":{"title":"Emmet Fox and the Sermon on the Mount","href":"fox.html","count":1,"prompts":[{"when":"2026-06-21T01:18","text":"You're building the Emmet Fox \"Sermon on the Mount\" post for my great-books series. Engine C, idea distillation. It belongs in the inner-life hub.\n\nRULES: First read CANON.md (especially \"What the first posts taught us\"), then VOICE.md and STYLE.md, study tao-te-ching.html for the shell. Voice is the bar (write-post plus monotone test, plain spoken, never formal); open concrete; source the book yourself via sub-agents, never ask me; 20px gutter at 375px; real sourced thumbnail (named).\n\nSpine: a 1934 reading of Jesus's Sermon on the Mount through \"New Thought,\" the idea that your thoughts literally shape your reality and the Sermon is a practical manual for changing your life, not a moral scolding. \"The kingdom of heaven is within you\" read as literal mind-power.\n\nKeystones: New Thought's core (\"change your thinking and you change your life\"); the Sermon re-read as practical metaphysics (the Beatitudes as states of mind, \"resist not evil\" as non-resistance, the Lord's Prayer as a mental treatment); and \"the Golden Key,\" Fox's famous method, stop thinking about the problem and think about God instead.\n\nEngine C: distill Fox's interpretation. 1934, in copyright, quote for study. The hook the owner will love: this was a textbook of early AA, passed around before the Big Book existed, and shaped AA's \"God as you understand Him.\" Tie it to the AA history. Be honest that New Thought is contested (the line runs to \"The Secret\"); give the real value and the overreach both.\n\nSHIP: add it to its hub, not a homepage card. In tools/gen-hubs.mjs flip the \"Emmet Fox, The Sermon on the Mount\" coming-soon line in the inner-life hub to a live entry (href, title, thumb, ~15-20 word description), then run `node tools/gen-hubs.mjs` and `node tools/build-search-index.mjs`. Add the og:image, verify the 20px gutter at 375px, commit and push with explicit paths."}]},"frankl":{"title":"Man's Search for Meaning","href":"frankl.html","count":1,"prompts":[{"when":"2026-06-20T17:00","text":"You're building the Frankl post for my great-books series. Engine C, idea distillation (a modern single book, nothing to stack, so distill the load-bearing ideas in my voice anchored to short quotes).\n\nRULES: First read CANON.md (especially \"What the first posts taught us\" and \"Four approaches\" for Engine C), then VOICE.md and STYLE.md, study tao-te-ching.html for the shell. Follow the rules: voice is the bar (write-post plus monotone test, plain, warm, spoken, never formal); open concrete; source the book and its sources yourself, never ask me; 20px gutter at 375px; real sourced thumbnail (named); homepage card description ONE short hook line of about 15 words.\n\nSpine: in a Nazi death camp, the men who held on were the ones who kept a meaning, a why; meaning, not pleasure or power, is the deepest human drive, and it stays available even in suffering, through the one freedom no one can take, your choice of attitude.\n\nKeystones (state each plainly, anchor to a short quote and page): \"the last of the human freedoms is to choose one's attitude in any given set of circumstances,\" the real line; the three sources of meaning (a work or deed, love, and the stance you take toward unavoidable suffering); \"those who have a why to live can bear almost any how,\" which Frankl quotes from Nietzsche; logotherapy, meaning-centered therapy; and the paradox that happiness cannot be chased directly, it can only ensue.\n\nSpecial: do NOT use the misattributed \"between stimulus and response there is a space\" line, it is not actually Frankl's. Be honest that the camp is testimony, not a controlled experiment. Part 1 is the memoir, part 2 is the therapy. This ties straight into the recovery and meaning thread already on the site.\n\nShip: card (ONE short hook line), og:image, real sourced thumbnail (named), 20px gutter at 375px, write-post self-edit, commit and push with explicit paths."}]},"grand-inquisitor":{"title":"The Grand Inquisitor","href":"grand-inquisitor.html","count":1,"prompts":[{"when":"2026-06-21T01:16","text":"You're building the Dostoevsky \"Grand Inquisitor\" post for my great-books series. Engine B, a one-reading walk through that chapter (and \"Rebellion\" before it) from The Brothers Karamazov. It belongs in the power-story-love hub.\n\nRULES: First read CANON.md (especially \"What the first posts taught us\"), then VOICE.md and STYLE.md, study tao-te-ching.html with js/tao*.js. Voice is the bar (write-post plus monotone test, plain spoken, never formal); open concrete; source the translations yourself via sub-agents, never ask me; 20px gutter at 375px; real sourced thumbnail (named).\n\nSpine: the most powerful argument against God ever written, in the mouth of a believer. Christ returns during the Inquisition and is arrested by the Grand Inquisitor, who accuses him of cruelly burdening humanity with freedom, which most people cannot bear. The Church has \"corrected\" his work with miracle, mystery, and authority (bread and chains). Would people rather be free, or fed and ruled?\n\nKeystones: Ivan's \"Rebellion\" (the suffering of children, \"I return the ticket\"); the Inquisitor's indictment (freedom versus bread; miracle, mystery, authority); \"if God does not exist, everything is permitted\"; Christ's only answer, a silent kiss.\n\nEngine B: walk it in one strong translation, stack sidebars on famous lines. Translations: Constance Garnett (PD), Pevear and Volokhonsky, McDuff, Avsey. Give Ivan's case full force, then Dostoevsky's reply (the kiss, Zosima).\n\nSHIP: add it to its hub, not a homepage card. In tools/gen-hubs.mjs flip the \"Dostoevsky, the Grand Inquisitor\" coming-soon line in the power-story-love hub to a live entry (href, title, thumb, ~15-20 word description), then run `node tools/gen-hubs.mjs` and `node tools/build-search-index.mjs`. Add the og:image, verify the 20px gutter at 375px, commit and push with explicit paths."}]},"in-praise-of-shadows":{"title":"In Praise of Shadows","href":"in-praise-of-shadows.html","count":1,"prompts":[{"when":"2026-06-21T01:17","text":"You're building the Japanese-aesthetics post for my great-books series, on Tanizaki's In Praise of Shadows with Okakura's The Book of Tea. Engine C, idea distillation. It belongs in the power-story-love hub.\n\nRULES: First read CANON.md (especially \"What the first posts taught us\"), then VOICE.md and STYLE.md, study tao-te-ching.html for the shell. Voice is the bar (write-post plus monotone test, plain spoken, never formal); open concrete and sensory; source the essays yourself via sub-agents, never ask me; 20px gutter at 375px; real sourced thumbnail (named).\n\nSpine: a Japanese aesthetic that is the opposite of the Western one, beauty in shadow, imperfection, transience, and emptiness, not in light, symmetry, and permanence. Tanizaki mourns the electric light flooding out the shadows Japanese beauty lived in; Okakura finds the whole philosophy in a cup of tea.\n\nKeystones: wabi-sabi (beauty in imperfection, impermanence, incompleteness); the beauty of shadow, patina, and the worn; the tea ceremony as the worship of the imperfect; ma, the meaningful empty space; mono no aware, the gentle ache of things passing.\n\nEngine C: distill the aesthetic from the two short essays (Tanizaki 1933, Okakura 1906). This rhymes hard with the live Spirituality of Imperfection post, beauty in the cracks; draw that line.\n\nSHIP: add it to its hub, not a homepage card. In tools/gen-hubs.mjs flip the \"In Praise of Shadows\" coming-soon line in the power-story-love hub to a live entry (href, title, thumb, ~15-20 word description), then run `node tools/gen-hubs.mjs` and `node tools/build-search-index.mjs`. Add the og:image, verify the 20px gutter at 375px, commit and push with explicit paths."}]},"kama-sutra":{"title":"The Kama Sutra, Side by Side","href":"kama-sutra.html","count":1,"prompts":[{"when":"2026-06-21T01:17","text":"You're building the Kama Sutra post for my great-books series. Engine A, the translation stack. It belongs in the power-story-love hub.\n\nRULES: First read CANON.md (especially \"What the first posts taught us\"), then VOICE.md and STYLE.md, study tao-te-ching.html with js/tao*.js, clone that architecture. Voice is the bar (write-post plus monotone test, plain spoken, never formal); open concrete; source the translations yourself via sub-agents, never ask me; 20px gutter at 375px; real sourced thumbnail (named, chosen with taste, classical Indian art, not the lurid).\n\nSpine: the most misunderstood book in the world. Not a sex manual but a guide to the art of living well, of which erotic love is one civilized part. Kama (pleasure) is one of the four legitimate aims of a Hindu life, alongside dharma, artha, and moksha, and Vatsyayana treats it as a skill cultivated with taste and mutual delight.\n\nKeystones: kama as one of the four aims of life (the frame that recontextualizes everything); the \"sixty-four arts\" a cultured person learns (music, cooking, conversation); courtship, marriage, and living as a couple, which is most of the book; the famous positions, which are one chapter of seven; its surprisingly modern attention to a woman's pleasure and consent.\n\nEngine A: stack translations, and the translation story IS the spine. Burton's 1883 version (PD) is filtered through Victorian prudery and made exotic on purpose, against Wendy Doniger and Sudhir Kakar's accurate modern translation. Sanskrit source line. Clear up the cliche; handle with maturity, not titillation.\n\nSHIP: add it to its hub, not a homepage card. In tools/gen-hubs.mjs flip the \"The Kama Sutra\" coming-soon line in the power-story-love hub to a live entry (href, title, thumb, ~15-20 word description), then run `node tools/gen-hubs.mjs` and `node tools/build-search-index.mjs`. Add the og:image, verify the 20px gutter at 375px, commit and push with explicit paths."}]},"machiavelli":{"title":"The Prince, Power Without the Moralizing","href":"machiavelli.html","count":1,"prompts":[{"when":"2026-06-21T01:17","text":"You're building the Machiavelli \"Prince\" post for my great-books series. Engine B, walk the argument. It belongs in the power-story-love hub.\n\nRULES: First read CANON.md (especially \"What the first posts taught us\"), then VOICE.md and STYLE.md, study tao-te-ching.html with js/tao*.js. Voice is the bar (write-post plus monotone test, plain spoken, never formal); open concrete; source the translations yourself via sub-agents, never ask me; 20px gutter at 375px; real sourced thumbnail (named).\n\nSpine: politics as it actually is, not as it should be. A ruler who insists on being good among the wicked will be destroyed, so the prince must \"learn how not to be good,\" and use it when he must. The first honest manual of power, stripped of moralizing.\n\nKeystones: \"better to be feared than loved, if you cannot be both\"; virtu (skill, nerve) against fortuna (luck, \"fortune is a woman\"); the lion and the fox; cruelty \"well used\"; why a name for meanness beats one for generosity; and the famous misquote, he never quite writes \"the ends justify the means,\" so handle that.\n\nEngine B: walk it, stack sidebars on the famous lines and misquotes. Translations: Marriott (1908 PD), Mansfield, Bull, Codevilla. Name the live debate: cynical evil, honest realism, or a republican's coded warning; present the range.\n\nSHIP: add it to its hub, not a homepage card. In tools/gen-hubs.mjs flip the \"Machiavelli, The Prince\" coming-soon line in the power-story-love hub to a live entry (href, title, thumb, ~15-20 word description), then run `node tools/gen-hubs.mjs` and `node tools/build-search-index.mjs`. Add the og:image, verify the 20px gutter at 375px, commit and push with explicit paths."}]},"meditations":{"title":"The Meditations of Marcus Aurelius, Side by Side","href":"meditations.html","count":1,"prompts":[{"when":"2026-06-20T16:59","text":"You're building the Marcus Aurelius, Meditations post for my great-books series. Engine A, the translation stack (short aphoristic entries, many translations, ideal for it).\n\nRULES: First read CANON.md (especially \"What the first posts taught us\" and \"The map\"), then VOICE.md and STYLE.md, study tao-te-ching.html with js/tao*.js, clone that architecture. Follow the rules: voice is the bar (write-post plus monotone test, plain spoken, never formal); open concrete; source the translations yourself via sub-agents, never ask me; 20px gutter at 375px; real sourced thumbnail (named); homepage card description ONE short hook line of about 15 words.\n\nThe hook: this was the private journal of the most powerful man in the world, the Roman emperor, writing notes to himself he never meant anyone to read, mostly about staying humble, doing his duty, and the fact that he would soon be dead.\n\nSpine: you control almost nothing except your own judgments; peace comes from accepting what you cannot control, doing the work in front of you, and remembering how short life is. We are disturbed not by things but by our opinions about them.\n\nKeystones: \"You have power over your mind, not outside events; realize this, and you will find strength\"; the dichotomy of control (lived from Epictetus); \"The impediment to action advances action; what stands in the way becomes the way\"; the view from above (the cosmic zoom-out); memento mori, you could leave life right now; \"Waste no more time arguing about what a good man should be; be one.\"\n\nSplits to stack: the Greek terms behind the calm and how translators render them. Translations (all fair game, name each): George Long (public domain), Gregory Hays (the beloved modern), Robin Hard, Maxwell Staniforth, Martin Hammond, Farquharson.\n\nShip: card (ONE short hook line), og:image, real sourced thumbnail (named), 20px gutter at 375px, write-post self-edit, commit and push with explicit paths."}]},"modern-teachers":{"title":"The Modern Teachers","href":"modern-teachers.html","count":1,"prompts":[{"when":"2026-06-21T01:18","text":"You're building the \"Modern Teachers\" post for my great-books series. Engine C, a distillation survey, one post, five teachers. It belongs in the inner-life hub.\n\nRULES: First read CANON.md (especially \"What the first posts taught us\"), then VOICE.md and STYLE.md, study tao-te-ching.html for the shell. Voice is the bar (write-post plus monotone test, plain spoken, never formal); open concrete; source the books yourself via sub-agents, never ask me; 20px gutter at 375px; real sourced thumbnail (named).\n\nSpine: how Eastern thought got translated, popularized, and sometimes distorted for the West, by a handful of charismatic teachers who each kept one idea and dropped the rest.\n\nThe five and their one teaching: Alan Watts (\"you are it,\" the universe looking at itself, the bridge to Zen and Tao); Krishnamurti (\"truth is a pathless land,\" drop every method and guru, including me); Ram Dass, Be Here Now (presence, the psychedelic-to-devotional turn); Eckhart Tolle, The Power of Now (you are not your mind, the pain-body); Gurdjieff and Ouspensky, the Fourth Way (most people are asleep machines, \"self-remembering\" wakes you).\n\nEngine C: distill each teacher's core idea plus the through-line (presence, ego-dissolution, waking up), and be honest about the guru problem, some were frauds or abusers, so separate the teaching from the teacher.\n\nSHIP: add it to its hub, not a homepage card. In tools/gen-hubs.mjs flip the \"The Modern Teachers\" coming-soon line in the inner-life hub to a live entry (href, title, thumb, ~15-20 word description), then run `node tools/gen-hubs.mjs` and `node tools/build-search-index.mjs`. Add the og:image, verify the 20px gutter at 375px, commit and push with explicit paths."}]},"odyssey":{"title":"The Odyssey, the Long Way Home","href":"odyssey.html","count":1,"prompts":[{"when":"2026-06-20T17:00","text":"You're building the Odyssey post for my great-books series. Engine B, walk it in one great translation (Emily Wilson's 2017 version is the modern landmark, feature it).\n\nRULES: First read CANON.md (especially \"What the first posts taught us\" and \"The map\"), then VOICE.md and STYLE.md, study tao-te-ching.html with js/tao*.js. Follow the rules: voice is the bar (write-post plus monotone test, plain spoken, never formal); open concrete; source the translations yourself via sub-agents, never ask me; 20px gutter at 375px; real sourced thumbnail (named); homepage card description ONE short hook line of about 15 words.\n\nSpine: not a moral code but the founding story of the Western imagination, the long journey home and what it costs. Endurance, cunning over brute force, the pull of home, and the question of who you still are when you finally get back.\n\nKeystones: Odysseus \"of many turns\" (polytropos); the monsters as temptations (the Lotus-eaters, the Cyclops, the Sirens, Scylla and Charybdis); \"Nobody\" outwitting the Cyclops, cunning beating strength; the underworld, where Achilles says he would rather be a slave alive than king of the dead; Penelope and the test of the bow; the recognition and the reckoning with the suitors.\n\nThe translation war is a great sidebar (like the Tao opening fan): Wilson's plain \"Tell me about a complicated man\" against the grand old openings (Pope public domain, Lattimore, Fitzgerald, Fagles). Note the oral-formula style, the repeated epithets. Focus on the Odyssey; a short note on the Iliad (rage and mortality) is enough.\n\nShip: card (ONE short hook line), og:image, real sourced thumbnail (named), 20px gutter at 375px, write-post self-edit, commit and push with explicit paths."}]},"perennial-philosophy":{"title":"The Perennial Philosophy","href":"perennial-philosophy.html","count":1,"prompts":[{"when":"2026-06-21T01:18","text":"You're building the \"Perennial Philosophy\" post for my great-books series. Engine C, idea distillation. It belongs in the inner-life hub.\n\nRULES: First read CANON.md (especially \"What the first posts taught us\"), then VOICE.md and STYLE.md, study tao-te-ching.html for the shell. Voice is the bar (write-post plus monotone test, plain spoken, never formal); open concrete; source the book yourself via sub-agents, never ask me; 20px gutter at 375px; real sourced thumbnail (named).\n\nSpine: beneath every religion, Huxley argues, is the same core. There is a divine Ground of all being; you can know it directly; your true self is one with it; and the point of life is that union. He stacks mystics from every tradition (Eckhart, the Upanishads, the Sufis, the Buddhists) to show they describe the same thing.\n\nKeystones: the divine Ground; \"tat tvam asi\" (that thou art) as the universal claim; the ego as the one obstacle; the agreement of the mystics across traditions.\n\nEngine C: distill. 1945. This is almost the secret thesis of the whole series, the convergence the other posts keep circling, so name that. But pressure-test it honestly: critics say Huxley cherry-picks and flattens real differences; the \"all religions are one\" claim is contested. Give both.\n\nSHIP: add it to its hub, not a homepage card. In tools/gen-hubs.mjs flip the \"Huxley, The Perennial Philosophy\" coming-soon line in the inner-life hub to a live entry (href, title, thumb, ~15-20 word description), then run `node tools/gen-hubs.mjs` and `node tools/build-search-index.mjs`. Add the og:image, verify the 20px gutter at 375px, commit and push with explicit paths."}]},"sapiens":{"title":"Sapiens","href":"sapiens.html","count":1,"prompts":[{"when":"2026-06-21T01:16","text":"You're building the Sapiens post for my great-books series. Engine C, idea distillation, handled skeptically. It belongs in the philosophy hub.\n\nRULES: First read CANON.md (especially \"What the first posts taught us\"), then VOICE.md and STYLE.md, study tao-te-ching.html for the shell. Voice is the bar (write-post plus monotone test, plain spoken, never formal); open concrete; source the book yourself via sub-agents, never ask me; 20px gutter at 375px; real sourced thumbnail (named).\n\nSpine: what made one ape take over the planet? Not strength or raw intelligence, but the ability to believe in shared fictions, gods, nations, money, companies, that let millions of strangers cooperate.\n\nKeystones: imagined orders (money, religion, nations are stories we agree to believe); the cognitive revolution; agriculture as \"history's biggest fraud\" (wheat tamed us, the average farmer's life got worse); the claim progress hasn't made us happier; the coming end of Homo sapiens by bioengineering.\n\nEngine C, but skeptical, this is the truth-over-narrative lane. Sapiens is gripping and a generation's worldview, and historians say it overreaches and over-tidies. That tension is the post, not a flaw to hide. 2011.\n\nSHIP: add it to its hub, not a homepage card. In tools/gen-hubs.mjs flip the \"Sapiens\" coming-soon line in the philosophy hub to a live entry (href, title, thumb, ~15-20 word description), then run `node tools/gen-hubs.mjs` and `node tools/build-search-index.mjs`. Add the og:image, verify the 20px gutter at 375px, commit and push with explicit paths."}]},"sounds-made-up":{"title":"The Physics That Sounds Made Up","href":"sounds-made-up.html","count":1,"prompts":[{"when":"2026-06-21T03:24","text":"Can we make a blog post tackling the biggest, most important aspects of quantum physics, following my voice.md very closely, and using very smart analogies to perfectly explain each quantum principle to newbies one at a time? Like entanglement, and space and time itself and its relation to speed. And you take the lead and don't let me guide the wrong way; you may have a better approach or idea or set of things to talk about in this post. Also I want to include images in this post pretty frequently to help explain and keep the reader's attention."}]},"spirituality-of-imperfection":{"title":"The Spirituality of Imperfection","href":"spirituality-of-imperfection.html","count":2,"prompts":[{"when":"2026-06-20T03:55","text":"You're building a post for my \"great books, made learn-from-able\" series. This one is The Spirituality of Imperfection by Ernest Kurtz and Katherine Ketcham (1992). Approach C, the Idea Distillation. This is the capstone; do it last, because it ties the whole series together.\n\nVOICE IS THE BAR. Read CANON.md first (especially \"What the first posts taught us\"), then VOICE.md and STYLE.md. Study tao-te-ching.html for the shell and kit. write-post skill, monotone test, plain warm spoken, concrete opener. Unlike the Deutsch post, this one IS a wisdom book, so give it the warm, personal, story-first treatment, not the cool argument-map look.\n\nThere are no competing translations (it was written once, in English), so use Approach C: state each load-bearing idea plainly in my voice, anchored to a short quote with its page or chapter. deep-research skill, dossier in research/spirituality-of-imperfection/. Source the book and its embedded sources yourself; do not ask me to fetch copies.\n\nContext worth knowing: Ernest Kurtz also wrote Not-God, the definitive history of Alcoholics Anonymous, so this connects directly to the AA posts on the site. The book teaches spirituality through stories drawn from many traditions (Hasidic tales, the desert fathers, Zen koans, Sufi stories, and AA).\n\nThe spine (diagnosis and prescription): the modern demand to be perfect and in control, and the denial of our own limits, is what kills the spiritual life; spirituality is found precisely in accepting imperfection. \"To be human is to be imperfect,\" and that imperfection is the doorway, not the obstacle.\n\nLoad-bearing ideas (verify and expand, state each plainly, anchor with a short quote):\n- The thesis: spirituality begins with accepting that our fractured, imperfect being simply is.\n- Imperfection as the spiritual ground; the wisdom traditions agree we are limited, and that this is the way in.\n- The story, not the doctrine, is the native form of spiritual wisdom: we discover who we are by telling our own.\n- \"Not-God,\" Kurtz's foundational AA insight: the first and essential message is that you are not God, not in control. The root of both the addiction and the recovery.\n- The specific qualities the book maps (release, gratitude, humility, tolerance, forgiveness, being-at-home), each told through a tale.\n- Spirituality as experience, not belief; the difference from religion.\n\nReproduce a few of the embedded cross-tradition stories (they are the best part), each attributed. The interactive element could be a small gallery of those tales, stories from very different traditions that all teach the same thing.\n\nThis is the capstone because it names the thread under the whole series: the convergence on imperfection, ego, and limitation that shows up as self-centeredness in AA, haumai in Sikhism, anatta in Buddhism, pride in Christianity. Let the post explicitly tie the series together and reference the other posts.\n\nWhen built and self-edited, add the homepage card, og:image, real sourced thumbnail (named). Verify 20px gutter at 375px. Commit and push with explicit paths."},{"when":"2026-06-20T11:22","text":"sources should be in a drop down box like my other posts"}]},"symposium":{"title":"Plato's Symposium, the Ladder of Love","href":"symposium.html","count":1,"prompts":[{"when":"2026-06-21T01:17","text":"You're building the Plato \"Symposium\" post for my great-books series. Engine B, a one-reading walk through the dialogue. It belongs in the power-story-love hub.\n\nRULES: First read CANON.md (especially \"What the first posts taught us\"), then VOICE.md and STYLE.md, study tao-te-ching.html with js/tao*.js. Voice is the bar (write-post plus monotone test, plain spoken, never formal); open concrete; source the translations yourself via sub-agents, never ask me; 20px gutter at 375px; real sourced thumbnail (named).\n\nSpine: a drinking party where each guest gives a speech on love, climbing from the crude to the sublime. The foundational Western text on what love is, and the source of \"Platonic love,\" which almost nobody has right.\n\nKeystones: Aristophanes' myth (humans were once double, split by Zeus, so love is the search for your other half); Diotima's ladder of love, relayed by Socrates (from one beautiful body, to all bodies, to beautiful souls, to Beauty itself); love as the child of Poverty and Resource; drunk Alcibiades crashing in to praise, and confess he was refused by, Socrates.\n\nEngine B: walk it in one strong translation, stack sidebars on the famous bits. Translations: Jowett (PD), Nehamas and Woodruff, Gill.\n\nSHIP: add it to its hub, not a homepage card. In tools/gen-hubs.mjs flip the \"Plato's Symposium\" coming-soon line in the power-story-love hub to a live entry (href, title, thumb, ~15-20 word description), then run `node tools/gen-hubs.mjs` and `node tools/build-search-index.mjs`. Add the og:image, verify the 20px gutter at 375px, commit and push with explicit paths."}]},"the-body-rhymes":{"title":"The Body Rhymes","href":"the-body-rhymes.html","count":1,"prompts":[{"when":"2026-06-21T14:49","text":"Post about weird stuff that happens to almost everyone very young and very old, that should really surprise middle-aged people in their 30s and 40s without babies. Like with babies, it's normal to turn yellow at the beginning and to have blood and milk come from the nipples, for example. But then look at the old side too. Now, don't let me direct this thing; I think you may have ideas to steer this post in the best direction. What are your ideas?"}]},"the-far-side-of-the-body":{"title":"The Far Side of the Body","href":"the-far-side-of-the-body.html","count":3,"prompts":[{"when":"2026-06-18T02:00","text":"A blog post on the top 10 most common diseases where people live in extreme constant pain. Ask me questions."},{"when":"2026-06-18T03:13","text":"Could we make this post better? Like a total change, or an addition, or a pivot here? Not a good post... totally unbalanced. What do you think?"},{"when":"2026-06-18T12:06","text":"Okay, make sure the thumbnail has a real image, and a nice one."}]},"the-other-hours":{"title":"The Other Hours","href":"the-other-hours.html","count":2,"prompts":[{"when":"2026-06-21T14:49","text":"Add a post like my Big Enough and cardio-and-stretching posts, but for all the other stuff for health. One example is sauna and cold plunge, but I want you to cover it all. You give me ideas."},{"when":"2026-06-21T15:52","text":"Okay now maybe I get all these posts into a collection post like I did the religious books?"}]},"william-james":{"title":"The Varieties of Religious Experience","href":"william-james.html","count":1,"prompts":[{"when":"2026-06-21T01:17","text":"You're building the William James post for my great-books series. Engine C, idea distillation. It belongs in the inner-life hub.\n\nRULES: First read CANON.md (especially \"What the first posts taught us\"), then VOICE.md and STYLE.md, study tao-te-ching.html for the shell. Voice is the bar (write-post plus monotone test, plain spoken, never formal); open concrete; source the book yourself via sub-agents, never ask me; 20px gutter at 375px; real sourced thumbnail (named).\n\nSpine: study religion not as doctrine but as experience, the actual conversions, mystical states, and feelings people report. James, a scientist, takes them seriously as data, and judges them by their fruits, not their creeds.\n\nKeystones: the \"sick soul\" versus the \"healthy-minded\" (the once-born and twice-born); conversion as the divided self made whole; the four marks of mystical experience (ineffability, noetic quality, transiency, passivity); pragmatism, \"by their fruits ye shall know them.\"\n\nEngine C: distill. 1902, public domain. The hook the owner cares about: this is the book behind AA. Bill Wilson read it right after Towns Hospital, and the Big Book's \"spiritual experience\" language comes partly from James. Tie it to the AA history on the site.\n\nSHIP: add it to its hub, not a homepage card. In tools/gen-hubs.mjs flip the \"William James, The Varieties of Religious Experience\" coming-soon line in the inner-life hub to a live entry (href, title, thumb, ~15-20 word description), then run `node tools/gen-hubs.mjs` and `node tools/build-search-index.mjs`. Add the og:image, verify the 20px gutter at 375px, commit and push with explicit paths."}]},"wisdom-never-written-down":{"title":"The Wisdom Never Written Down","href":"wisdom-never-written-down.html","count":1,"prompts":[{"when":"2026-06-21T01:18","text":"You're building the \"wisdom never written down\" post for my great-books series. An essay, not a translation stack. It belongs in the religion hub.\n\nRULES: First read CANON.md (especially \"What the first posts taught us\"), then VOICE.md and STYLE.md, study tao-te-ching.html for the shell. Voice is the bar (write-post plus monotone test, plain spoken, never formal); open concrete; source the material yourself via sub-agents, never ask me; 20px gutter at 375px; real sourced thumbnail (named).\n\nSpine: a \"great books\" series has a built-in blind spot, every tradition that never wrote a book. Name it honestly, and gather the wisdom that survives in other forms.\n\nCover: the limit (writing is a technology, and most human wisdom was oral, sung, danced, or carved, never written); the Aboriginal songlines (a map, a law, and a history sung across a continent); Native American oral traditions (the spoken treaty, the trickster tales); the African griot and the proverb; why these resist the \"stack the translations and break down the keystones\" format; and what we can still learn from them.\n\nEngine: a straight essay. This is the series being honest about its own shape. Respectful, never appropriative, lean on indigenous voices where you can.\n\nSHIP: add it to its hub, not a homepage card. In tools/gen-hubs.mjs flip the \"The wisdom never written down\" coming-soon line in the religion hub to a live entry (href, title, thumb, ~15-20 word description), then run `node tools/gen-hubs.mjs` and `node tools/build-search-index.mjs`. Add the og:image, verify the 20px gutter at 375px, commit and push with explicit paths."}]},"analects":{"title":"The Analects of Confucius, Side by Side","href":"analects.html","count":1,"prompts":[{"when":"2026-06-20T03:53","text":"You're building a post for my \"great books, made learn-from-able\" series. This one is The Analects of Confucius. Approach A, the Translation Stack, the same engine as the Tao Te Ching post.\n\nVOICE IS THE BAR. The first post in this series (Deutsch) shipped too formal and educational and had to be fixed; do not repeat that. Read CANON.md first (especially \"What the first posts taught us\"), then VOICE.md and STYLE.md, then study tao-te-ching.html with js/tao-data.js, js/tao-notes.js, js/tao.js. Write the prose with the write-post skill and run its monotone read-aloud test. Plain, warm, spoken, a smart friend telling you something true. Open concrete (an everyday example), never on an abstract claim.\n\nClone the Tao architecture: analects.html, js/analects-data.js, js/analects-notes.js, reusing the js/tao.js patterns. Run the deep-research skill and drop a dossier in research/analects/. Source the best translations yourself (including copyrighted ones), spawning parallel sub-agents to track them down; do not ask me to fetch copies.\n\nThe spine (diagnosis and prescription): a society falls apart when people abandon virtue and their roles; the repair is self-cultivation that ripples outward, from the person to the family to the state.\n\nKeystones (verify and expand):\n- 15.24, the self-summary: asked for one word to practice for life, \"Reciprocity (shu). Do not impose on others what you do not desire.\" The negative golden rule.\n- 2.4, the arc of a life: \"At fifteen I set my heart on learning... at seventy I could follow my heart's desire without overstepping.\"\n- 2.3, govern by virtue and ritual, not law and punishment.\n- 12.1, ren as self-mastery and returning to ritual.\n- 2.15, \"Learning without thought is labor lost; thought without learning is perilous.\"\n- 4.8, \"If a man hears the Way in the morning, he may die content in the evening.\"\n- 13.3, the rectification of names.\n- 1.2, filial piety as the root of humaneness.\n\nThe load-bearing untranslatables to stack (the Analects' dao and wu wei): ren (benevolence / humaneness / goodness / authoritative conduct), junzi (gentleman / exemplary person / superior man), li (ritual / rites / propriety), de (virtue / moral force), tian (heaven). Classical Chinese source line with gloss.\n\nTranslations to stack (all fair game, name every one): James Legge, Arthur Waley, D.C. Lau, Ezra Pound, Simon Leys, Edward Slingerland, Ames and Rosemont, Burton Watson, Annping Chin. Frame: more philosophical than religious; the Analects is fragments compiled by disciples, not a treatise, say so; Confucius calls himself a transmitter not an inventor (7.1).\n\nWhen built and self-edited against VOICE.md, add the homepage card, og:image, and a real sourced thumbnail (named, never generative). Verify at 375px that the gutter is 20px. Commit and push to main with explicit paths."}]},"aristotle":{"title":"Aristotle and the Good Life","href":"aristotle.html","count":1,"prompts":[{"when":"2026-06-20T16:59","text":"You're building the Aristotle's Ethics post for my great-books series. Engine B, walk the argument.\n\nRULES: First read CANON.md (especially \"What the first posts taught us\" and \"The map\"), then VOICE.md and STYLE.md, study tao-te-ching.html with js/tao*.js. Follow the rules: voice is the bar (write-post plus monotone test, plain spoken, never formal or academic, high risk here, keep it human); open concrete with an everyday analogy; source the translations yourself via sub-agents, never ask me; 20px gutter at 375px; real sourced thumbnail (named); homepage card description ONE short hook line of about 15 words.\n\nSpine: everyone wants to be happy, but they chase the wrong things (pleasure, money, status); real happiness is a whole life lived well, and you get there by building good habits.\n\nKeystones: eudaimonia (happiness as flourishing, not a feeling); the function argument (a good human does the human thing, reasoning, well); virtue as the mean between extremes (courage sits between cowardice and recklessness); virtue as habit (\"we are what we repeatedly do\"); practical wisdom (phronesis); friendship (books 8 and 9); and contemplation as the highest life (book 10).\n\nTerms to gloss in sidebars: eudaimonia (happiness / flourishing / well-being), arete (virtue / excellence), phronesis (practical wisdom), the doctrine of the mean.\n\nTranslations (all fair game, name each): Ross (public domain), Irwin, Crisp, Rowe, Bartlett and Collins, Sachs. Keep it concrete throughout (you learn courage the way you learn an instrument, by doing it badly until you do it well).\n\nShip: card (ONE short hook line), og:image, real sourced thumbnail (named), 20px gutter at 375px, write-post self-edit, commit and push with explicit paths."}]},"beginning-of-infinity":{"title":"The Beginning of Infinity, Mapped","href":"beginning-of-infinity.html","count":1,"prompts":[{"when":"2026-06-18T12:31","text":"You're building a post for my \"great books, made learn-from-able\" series. This one is David Deutsch's The Beginning of Infinity (2011). It uses Approach C, the Idea Distillation. It is the genre outlier in the series: secular epistemology and optimism, not a wisdom tradition, so it gets a crisp, modern, argument-mapping treatment, not the reverent scripture look.\n\nRead CANON.md first, then VOICE.md and STYLE.md. Study tao-te-ching.html only for the site shell and component kit; the engine here is different. There are no competing translations to stack (Deutsch wrote it once, in English). So the format inverts: each load-bearing idea is stated plainly in my voice, anchored to a short quote with its page or chapter, and placed in the book's argument. The interactive element should be an argument map (claim, why it holds, what follows), not a chapter explorer. Build whatever shell fits, reusing the palette, fonts, and kit.\n\nBefore building, run the deep-research skill and drop a dossier in research/beginning-of-infinity/. Be exact: Deutsch is alive and his readers (the Hacker News and rationalist crowd) are exacting. Get the epistemology right, do not conflate his Popperian conjecture-and-criticism view with Bayesianism, which he opposes. Adversarially fact-check.\n\nThe job: make someone who will never read five hundred pages actually grasp the four or five ideas that matter.\n\nThe load-bearing ideas (verify and expand):\n- Good explanations are \"hard to vary\" while still accounting for what they explain. His central, original criterion. The keystone.\n- The reach of explanations: good explanatory knowledge is universal, it travels far beyond the problem it was built for.\n- Fallibilism: there are no authoritative sources of knowledge and no certainty; knowledge grows by conjecture and criticism (Popper). Error-correction is everything.\n- \"Problems are inevitable. Problems are soluble.\" Every problem not forbidden by the laws of nature is soluble given the right knowledge.\n- The principle of optimism: all evils are caused by insufficient knowledge. Optimism is a stance, not a mood.\n- The jump to universality: alphabets, number systems, DNA, computers, systems that cross a threshold into unlimited reach. People as universal explainers, \"the beginning of infinity.\"\n- The critique of empiricism and inductivism: theories are not derived from observation, they are conjectured and tested.\n- Against \"Spaceship Earth\" and the principle of mediocrity: people are significant; knowledge, not the biosphere, is what sustains us.\n\nUse Deutsch's own chapter-end \"Summary,\" \"Terminology,\" and \"Meanings of 'the beginning of infinity'\" sections as scaffolding; they are his own self-distillations. All quotation is fair game, just locate every quote by page or chapter.\n\nMatch his energy: combative, precise, allergic to vagueness. When built and self-edited against VOICE.md, add the homepage card and og:image, commit and push to main with explicit paths."}]},"chemical-path":{"title":"The Chemical Path","href":"chemical-path.html","count":1,"prompts":[{"when":"2026-06-21T01:18","text":"You're building the \"Chemical Path\" post for my great-books series. Engine D, the practice mapped (the entheogen route to the mystical). It belongs in the inner-life hub.\n\nRULES: First read CANON.md (especially \"What the first posts taught us\" and \"Four approaches\" for Engine D), then VOICE.md and STYLE.md, study tao-te-ching.html for the shell. Voice is the bar (write-post plus monotone test, plain and practical, never formal or salesy); open concrete; source the books and studies yourself via sub-agents, never ask me; 20px gutter at 375px; real sourced thumbnail (named).\n\nSpine: the oldest and most direct route to the mystical experience is chemical, and science is rediscovering it. Map the path across the traditions, the classic account, and the modern evidence.\n\nCover: the entheogen traditions (peyote and the Native American Church, ayahuasca, the Eleusinian mysteries, psilocybin); Huxley's The Doors of Perception (mescaline, the brain as a \"reducing valve\"); Michael Pollan's How to Change Your Mind (the science, psilocybin for depression and end-of-life anxiety, the \"ego dissolution\" that looks like the mystics' union); and the honest risks (bad trips, the unprepared, the hype, the legal and medical reality).\n\nEngine D: what it is, the traditions, what the evidence really shows, the experience, the risks. Truth over narrative, real data and real overhype, do not cheerlead.\n\nSHIP: add it to its hub, not a homepage card. In tools/gen-hubs.mjs flip the \"The Chemical Path\" coming-soon line in the inner-life hub to a live entry (href, title, thumb, ~15-20 word description), then run `node tools/gen-hubs.mjs` and `node tools/build-search-index.mjs`. Add the og:image, verify the 20px gutter at 375px, commit and push with explicit paths."}]},"cults-the-cage":{"title":"When a Path Becomes a Cage","href":"cults-the-cage.html","count":1,"prompts":[{"when":"2026-06-21T01:18","text":"You're building the first cults post for my great-books series, \"how a path becomes a cage.\" Engine D, a clearly labeled case study, not an endorsement. It belongs in the inner-life hub.\n\nRULES: First read CANON.md (especially \"What the first posts taught us,\" \"Four approaches,\" and the gate), then VOICE.md and STYLE.md, study tao-te-ching.html for the shell. Voice is the bar (write-post plus monotone test, plain spoken, never formal or lurid); open concrete; source the material yourself via sub-agents, never ask me; 20px gutter at 375px; real sourced thumbnail (named).\n\nSpine: every cult began as a path to meaning. What turns a spiritual community into a prison? Map the mechanism first, then the cases.\n\nThe mechanism: Robert Lifton's eight criteria of thought reform (milieu control, loading the language, demand for purity, confession) and Steven Hassan's BITE model; love-bombing, the charismatic leader, the slow escalation, the engineered cost of leaving. The cases: Scientology (billion-year contracts, disconnection), NXIVM (the self-help company that branded women), Rajneesh and Osho, and the deadly end, Jonestown and Heaven's Gate.\n\nEngine D, case study. Respectful but unflinching, clear about the line between a demanding practice and a cage.\n\nSHIP: add it to its hub, not a homepage card. The inner-life hub has one combined \"Cults: the cage and the business\" coming-soon line in tools/gen-hubs.mjs; split it into two and make THIS one (the cage) a live entry (href, title, thumb, ~15-20 word description), leaving the business one as coming-soon. Run `node tools/gen-hubs.mjs` and `node tools/build-search-index.mjs`. Add the og:image, verify the 20px gutter at 375px, commit and push with explicit paths."}]},"dhammapada":{"title":"The Dhammapada, Side by Side","href":"dhammapada.html","count":1,"prompts":[{"when":"2026-06-18T12:31","text":"You're building a post for my \"great books, made learn-from-able\" series on this site. This one is the Dhammapada, the verse heart of the Buddhist Pali Canon. It uses Approach A, the Translation Stack, the same engine as the Tao Te Ching post.\n\nStart by reading CANON.md (the series brief), then VOICE.md and STYLE.md, then study the reference build: tao-te-ching.html with js/tao-data.js, js/tao-notes.js, js/tao.js. The Dhammapada post should clone that architecture: a dhammapada.html shell, js/dhammapada-data.js (the translations, verbatim), js/dhammapada-notes.js (the breakdowns), reusing the js/tao.js explorer patterns.\n\nBefore building, run the deep-research skill and drop a dossier in research/dhammapada/.\n\nThe text: 423 verses in 26 chapters (vaggas), the Buddha's teaching in verse, in Pali. Use Romanized Pali as the \"source\" slot the way the Tao post uses Chinese, with transliteration and gloss.\n\nThe spine (diagnosis and prescription): suffering comes from the untrained mind and from craving, hatred, and delusion; the cure is to train the mind, live ethically, and cool the craving. \"Mind precedes all things.\"\n\nKeystone verses to anchor the breakdowns on (verify and expand in research):\n- v1-2, the Twin Verses: \"Mind precedes all mental states,\" the whole psychology in two lines.\n- v5: \"Hatred is never appeased by hatred, by love alone,\" the ethical keystone.\n- v183: \"Not to do evil, to cultivate good, to purify the mind: this is the teaching of the Buddhas,\" the tradition's own self-summary.\n- v153-154, the house-builder verses, said to be the Buddha's words at awakening.\n- v277-279, the three marks: all conditioned things are impermanent (anicca), are suffering (dukkha), all things are not-self (anatta).\n- v103: \"He who conquers himself is the greater victor.\"\n- v21: \"Heedfulness is the path to the deathless\" (appamada).\n\nTranslation splits worth showing (the Pali equivalents of the Tao's dao and wu wei): dukkha (\"suffering\" vs \"unsatisfactoriness\" vs Thanissaro's \"stress\"), anatta (\"not-self\" vs \"no-self\"), dhamma, sankhara, nibbana.\n\nTranslations to stack (all sources are fair game, name every one): Max Muller (1881), Acharya Buddharakkhita, Thanissaro Bhikkhu, Gil Fronsdal, Eknath Easwaran, Juan Mascaro, Glenn Wallis, Daw Mya Tin, Ananda Maitreya, and others you find. Thanissaro and Buddharakkhita are freely redistributable via Access to Insight.\n\nFrame: the accessible heart of the older (Theravada) canon. Note where Mahayana would diverge, but anchor on the Pali Dhammapada. Use the Key / Complete / All view toggle like the Tao post; not every verse needs a breakdown, only the keystones.\n\nWhen it is built and self-edited against VOICE.md, add the homepage card and og:image, then commit and push to main with explicit paths."}]},"gita":{"title":"The Bhagavad Gita, Side by Side","href":"gita.html","count":1,"prompts":[{"when":"2026-06-20T03:54","text":"You're building a post for my \"great books, made learn-from-able\" series. This one is the Bhagavad Gita, the heart of Hindu scripture. Approach A, the Translation Stack.\n\nVOICE IS THE BAR. The first post (Deutsch) shipped too formal and had to be fixed; do not repeat that. Read CANON.md first (especially \"What the first posts taught us\"), then VOICE.md and STYLE.md, then study tao-te-ching.html and js/tao*.js. Write the prose with the write-post skill and run the monotone test. Plain, warm, spoken. Open concrete, never abstract.\n\nClone the Tao architecture: gita.html, js/gita-data.js, js/gita-notes.js. Run the deep-research skill, dossier in research/gita/. Source the best translations yourself, including copyrighted ones, via parallel sub-agents; do not ask me to fetch copies.\n\nThe setup is a story: Arjuna freezes on the battlefield, unwilling to fight a war that will kill his own kin, and Krishna talks him through how to act in a world of duty and loss. That dialogue is the whole book. The spine (diagnosis and prescription): we are bound by attachment to the results of our actions and by ignorance of the deathless Self; the way out is to act without grasping at outcomes (karma yoga), to love and surrender (bhakti), and to know the Self (jnana).\n\nKeystones (verify and expand):\n- 2.47, the self-summary: \"You have a right to your actions, but never to the fruits of your actions.\" Karma yoga, the load-bearing line.\n- 2.20 and 2.22, the deathless Self: \"as a man casts off worn-out clothes and takes new ones, so the Self casts off worn-out bodies.\" The teaching that dissolves Arjuna's grief.\n- 3.35 / 18.47, svadharma: \"better to do your own duty imperfectly than another's well.\"\n- 4.7-8, the avatar doctrine: \"Whenever dharma declines, I manifest to restore it.\"\n- Chapter 11, the theophany: Krishna's cosmic form, \"I am become Death, the shatterer of worlds\" (11.32).\n- 18.66, the final refuge verse: \"Abandon all dharmas and take refuge in me alone.\"\n\nWeave in the Upanishadic backdrop the Gita popularizes: the great sayings (mahavakyas) Tat tvam asi (\"That thou art\") and Aham Brahmasmi (\"I am Brahman\").\n\nUntranslatables to stack: dharma (duty / law / righteousness / the way things are), yoga (discipline / union / path), atman (Self / soul), karma (action), guna (the three qualities), Brahman. Sanskrit source line (Devanagari + transliteration).\n\nTranslations (all fair game, name each): Edwin Arnold (The Song Celestial), Kashinath Telang, Annie Besant, Prabhavananda and Isherwood, Eknath Easwaran, Barbara Stoler Miller, Stephen Mitchell, Winthrop Sargeant, Graham Schweig, Laurie Patton.\n\nName the sectarian contest (CANON.md says to): Advaita (Shankara, non-dual), Vishishtadvaita (Ramanuja, devotion), and Dvaita (Madhva, dualism) read the same verses oppositely. Situate the Gita as a 700-verse episode inside the Mahabharata. The war framing needs care: Gandhi read it as the inner battle, others literally; present the range.\n\nWhen built and self-edited, add the homepage card, og:image, real sourced thumbnail (named). Verify 20px gutter at 375px. Commit and push with explicit paths."}]},"guru-granth-sahib":{"title":"The Guru Granth Sahib, Side by Side","href":"guru-granth-sahib.html","count":1,"prompts":[{"when":"2026-06-20T03:54","text":"You're building a post for my \"great books, made learn-from-able\" series. This one is the Guru Granth Sahib, the scripture of Sikhism. Approach A, but it is a big text, so curate keystones rather than running the whole thing.\n\nVOICE IS THE BAR. Read CANON.md first (especially \"What the first posts taught us\"), then VOICE.md and STYLE.md, then study tao-te-ching.html and js/tao*.js. write-post skill, monotone test, plain warm spoken voice, concrete opener.\n\nClone the Tao architecture: guru-granth-sahib.html, js/ggs-data.js, js/ggs-notes.js. deep-research skill, dossier in research/guru-granth-sahib/. Source the best translations yourself via parallel sub-agents; do not ask me to fetch copies.\n\nOpen on the hook that reframes everything: the Guru Granth Sahib is treated as the eternal LIVING Guru. When Guru Gobind Singh died in 1708 he ended the line of human Gurus and named the book itself the Guru. It is enthroned, not just read. That changes what \"scripture\" even means.\n\nThe spine (diagnosis and prescription): we are separated from God by haumai (ego, self-centeredness, \"I am-ness\") and attachment; we return through naam (remembrance of the divine Name), honest living, and grace.\n\nKeystones (verify and expand):\n- The Mul Mantar, the self-summary and root creed that opens the book: \"Ik Onkar,\" One God, true by name, creator, without fear, without hatred, timeless, unborn, self-existent, known by grace.\n- Japji Sahib (Guru Nanak's morning prayer that opens the Granth) and its question: \"How to become truthful, how to tear away the veil of falsehood?\" Answer: by walking in the Hukam, the divine order.\n- The three pillars the text grounds: meditate on the Name, earn an honest living, share with others.\n- Nanak's rejection of caste, ritual, and empty pilgrimage: \"There is no Hindu, no Muslim,\" God is found in honest life, not ceremony.\n- The radical inclusion: the Granth contains hymns by Hindu and Muslim saints (Kabir, Ravidas, Farid), not just the Sikh Gurus. Highlight it.\n\nUntranslatables to stack: Naam (the Name / the divine identity), Hukam (divine order / will / command), Shabad (the Word / divine sound), haumai (ego / self-centeredness), sachiar (the true one), nadar (grace). Gurmukhi source line + transliteration. Note the text is multilingual.\n\nTranslations (all fair game, name each): Max Arthur Macauliffe, Gopal Singh, Manmohan Singh (the 8-volume standard), Sant Singh Khalsa (the widely used online translation), Nikky-Guninder Kaur Singh (modern, literary). Ernest Trumpp's notorious flawed Victorian version is useful only as a cautionary contrast, do not lean on its condescension.\n\nHandle with reverence; Sikhs treat the physical text with strict respect, and the post should reflect that care. The haumai diagnosis quietly rhymes with AA's \"self-centeredness is the root,\" but do not force the connection.\n\nWhen built and self-edited, add the homepage card, og:image, real sourced thumbnail (named). Verify 20px gutter at 375px. Commit and push with explicit paths."}]},"hebrew-bible":{"title":"The Hebrew Bible, Side by Side","href":"hebrew-bible.html","count":1,"prompts":[{"when":"2026-06-20T03:54","text":"You're building a post for my \"great books, made learn-from-able\" series. This one is the Hebrew Bible (the Tanakh), read as Judaism reads it. Approach A, curated keystones from a large text. Do this before the Christian Bible post; that one will build on this.\n\nVOICE IS THE BAR. Read CANON.md first (especially \"What the first posts taught us\"), then VOICE.md and STYLE.md, study tao-te-ching.html and js/tao*.js. write-post skill, monotone test, plain warm spoken, concrete opener.\n\nClone the Tao architecture: hebrew-bible.html, js/hebrew-bible-data.js, js/hebrew-bible-notes.js. deep-research skill, dossier in research/hebrew-bible/. Source the best translations yourself via parallel sub-agents; do not ask me to fetch copies.\n\nPitch the post on what is distinctively JEWISH about reading this text, not the Christian Old Testament lens: covenant, peoplehood, law, this-worldly ethics, and the text read through the rabbis (the Oral Torah), never alone. No Christ-typology, no original-sin emphasis.\n\nThe spine (diagnosis and prescription): a people keeps straying from the covenant and from justice; the repair is return (teshuvah), keeping the commandments, and pursuing justice as a holy people. This-world, not the afterlife.\n\nKeystones (verify and expand):\n- Hillel's self-summary (Talmud, Shabbat 31a): \"What is hateful to you, do not do to your neighbor. That is the whole Torah; the rest is commentary. Go and learn.\" Use it as the framing.\n- The Shema (Deut 6:4): \"Hear, O Israel: the LORD our God, the LORD is One,\" with \"love the LORD your God with all your heart.\" The creed.\n- Genesis 1: creation, humans in the image of God (1:27). Translation fork: \"In the beginning God created\" vs \"When God began to create.\"\n- Exodus: the founding event of peoplehood, the burning bush and the divine name \"Ehyeh asher ehyeh\" (Ex 3:14), the Decalogue (Ex 20).\n- Leviticus 19:18: \"love your neighbor as yourself,\" inside the Holiness Code.\n- Deuteronomy 16:20: \"Justice, justice shall you pursue.\"\n- Micah 6:8: \"do justice, love mercy, walk humbly with your God.\"\n- Ecclesiastes (Kohelet): \"hevel,\" vanity or breath, the wisdom counterweight.\n\nUntranslatables and forks to stack: the Tetragrammaton YHWH (\"the LORD\" / \"Yahweh\" / \"the Eternal\" / unpronounced), torah (law / teaching / instruction, \"teaching\" is the truer sense), nephesh (soul / life / being), tzedek (justice / righteousness), hevel. Hebrew source line (pointed) + transliteration.\n\nTranslations (all fair game, name each): JPS 1917 and NJPS 1985 (the Jewish standards), Robert Alter (the literary landmark, feature it), Everett Fox (echoes the Hebrew syntax), KJV (the famous English cadence), Young's Literal, Koren. Name the Jewish framing: Tanakh = Torah, Nevi'im, Ketuvim; the written and oral Torah are inseparable. The contest with the Christian reading is a teaching point (Isaiah 7:14 almah, \"young woman\" vs \"virgin\"). Avoid supersessionism; handle with respect.\n\nWhen built and self-edited, add the homepage card, og:image, real sourced thumbnail (named). Verify 20px gutter at 375px. Commit and push with explicit paths."}]},"marx":{"title":"Marx and the Gravediggers","href":"marx.html","count":1,"prompts":[{"when":"2026-06-20T16:59","text":"You're building the Marx post for my great-books series. Engine B, walk the argument of The Communist Manifesto (short and punchy), with a little of Capital. He is a dissenter, like Nietzsche; let his critique stand, and be honest about the catastrophe done in his name.\n\nRULES: First read CANON.md (especially \"What the first posts taught us\" and \"The map\"), then VOICE.md and STYLE.md, study tao-te-ching.html with js/tao*.js. Follow the rules: voice is the bar (write-post plus the monotone read-aloud test, plain spoken, never formal); open concrete with an everyday analogy; source the texts yourself via sub-agents, never ask me; 20px gutter at 375px; real sourced thumbnail (named); homepage card description ONE short hook line of about 15 words.\n\nSpine: history is driven by class struggle, not ideas or great men; capitalism, for all its dynamism, splits society into owners and workers, alienates the worker from what he makes, and breeds its own gravediggers. The cure he predicts: the workers seize the means of production and abolish private property, ending class itself.\n\nKeystones: \"The history of all hitherto existing society is the history of class struggles\"; \"All that is solid melts into air\"; \"Workers of the world, unite, you have nothing to lose but your chains\"; alienation (the worker makes the thing but cannot afford it); ideology, the ruling ideas are the ideas of the ruling class; and from Capital, briefly, commodity fetishism and surplus value.\n\nEditions all fair game (the Moore 1888 English of the Manifesto is public domain).\n\nSpecial, truth over narrative: let the analytic power of the critique land, AND keep the twentieth-century record visible, the regimes built in his name and their body count. He is not Stalin, but the disaster is part of the honest story. Concrete: the factory floor, the thing the worker builds and cannot buy.\n\nShip: card (ONE short hook line), og:image, real sourced thumbnail (named), 20px gutter at 375px, write-post self-edit, commit and push with explicit paths."}]},"meditation":{"title":"Meditation, Mapped","href":"meditation.html","count":1,"prompts":[{"when":"2026-06-20T12:52","text":"You're building the flagship Meditation post for my \"great books, made learn-from-able\" series. This is the pilot for Engine D (the practice mapped), and the most important post in the batch, so get it right. One consolidated post on all kinds of meditation: the truth of the benefits and how to actually get them. There is no single text, so map the practices.\n\nRULES: First read CANON.md (especially \"What the first posts taught us,\" \"Four approaches\" for Engine D, and \"The map\"), then VOICE.md and STYLE.md, study tao-te-ching.html for the shell and kit. Follow the rules hard, voice most of all: write the prose with the write-post skill and run its monotone read-aloud test, plain, warm, and practical (your Big Enough and Still Moving lane), never formal or salesy; open concrete with an everyday analogy; source the studies and the primary instructions yourself via sub-agents, never ask me; 20px gutter at 375px; real sourced thumbnail (named); homepage card description ONE short hook line of about 15 words.\n\nCover the major techniques, what each actually is: TM (mantra), vipassana and insight (Goenka, the Satipatthana Sutta), mindfulness and MBSR (Kabat-Zinn), zazen (Zen), loving-kindness (metta), breathwork and pranayama, the body scan, Christian contemplative prayer (centering prayer, the Jesus prayer), Sufi dhikr, Tibetan tonglen.\n\nThe truth (adversarially fact-check, this is the truth-over-narrative lane): what the evidence actually supports versus the hype. Lean on the strong reviews (the Goyal 2014 JAMA meta-analysis found moderate evidence for anxiety, depression, and pain, and little for the rest), the honest adverse-effects research (Willoughby Britton and Cheetah House, meditation can destabilize some people), and the overclaiming of the meditation industry and of TM's grander cosmic claims (yogic flying). TM folds in here, with that honest framing.\n\nThe how-to: the actual core instruction for the main techniques, posture, what to do with the mind, how long, the common mistakes, so a reader can truly begin.\n\nEngine D structure per technique: what it is, where it came from, what it claims, what the evidence shows, and how to do the core of it. Consider an interactive technique comparison.\n\nShip: card (ONE short hook line), og:image, real sourced thumbnail (named), 20px gutter at 375px, write-post self-edit, commit and push to main with explicit paths."}]},"mill":{"title":"On Liberty, and the Only Reason to Stop You","href":"mill.html","count":1,"prompts":[{"when":"2026-06-20T16:59","text":"You're building the Mill, On Liberty post for my great-books series. Engine B, walk the argument (it is short and one sustained case).\n\nRULES: First read CANON.md (especially \"What the first posts taught us\" and \"The map\"), then VOICE.md and STYLE.md, study tao-te-ching.html with js/tao*.js. Follow the rules: voice is the bar (write-post plus monotone test, plain spoken, never formal); open concrete; source the text yourself, never ask me; 20px gutter at 375px; real sourced thumbnail (named); homepage card description ONE short hook line of about 15 words.\n\nSpine: the only reason society may rightly coerce an adult against their will is to stop them harming others; over himself, the individual is sovereign. The real danger in a democracy is not a tyrant but the tyranny of the majority, social pressure crushing the odd and the dissenting.\n\nKeystones: the harm principle (\"the only purpose for which power can be rightfully exercised over any member of a civilized community, against his will, is to prevent harm to others\"); the tyranny of the majority; the case for near-total free speech (we may be silencing the truth; even a false opinion sharpens the true one; and a true opinion never challenged decays into \"dead dogma\"); individuality and \"experiments in living\" as part of a good life.\n\nThe text is public domain (1859), English original, so no translation stack; this is a one-reading walk.\n\nSpecial: it is the source code of the modern open society and today's free-speech fights; let the reader feel how downstream we still are. Steelman the hard part (the harm principle's fuzzy edges) before answering. Concrete throughout.\n\nShip: card (ONE short hook line), og:image, real sourced thumbnail (named), 20px gutter at 375px, write-post self-edit, commit and push with explicit paths."}]},"nagarjuna":{"title":"Nagarjuna and the Emptiness of Everything","href":"nagarjuna.html","count":1,"prompts":[{"when":"2026-06-20T03:54","text":"You're building a post for my \"great books, made learn-from-able\" series. This one is Nagarjuna's Mulamadhyamakakarika, the foundation of Madhyamaka Buddhist philosophy, in Jay Garfield's translation (The Fundamental Wisdom of the Middle Way). Approach B, the One-Reading Walk. This is the hardest content in the series.\n\nVOICE IS THE BAR, and this is the maximum-danger post for the \"too educational\" failure. Read CANON.md first (especially \"What the first posts taught us\"), then VOICE.md and STYLE.md, study tao-te-ching.html and js/tao*.js for the shell and the breakdown idiom. write-post skill, monotone test. Use concrete everyday analogies relentlessly (the chariot and its parts, a forest that is \"empty\" of being one thing yet full of trees); if a smart friend cannot follow a paragraph on one read, rewrite it. Do not lapse into Buddhist-studies register.\n\nBuild a one-reading walk: Garfield as the spine (his verse-by-verse commentary is why his edition is the standard), and unpack the argument. This text is technical argument, not story or devotion, so track the logical moves, the reductios, not just the verses. Use the multi-translation stack only as sidebars on the few pivotal verses. deep-research skill, dossier in research/nagarjuna/. Source the editions yourself via parallel sub-agents; do not ask me to fetch copies.\n\nThe spine (diagnosis and prescription): we suffer because we grasp things, and ourselves, as having svabhava, an independent fixed essence; that grasping is the root delusion. The cure is to see emptiness (sunyata): nothing exists independently, because everything arises dependently. Emptiness is not nothingness; it is the absence of independent essence, which is exactly what makes change and liberation possible.\n\nKeystone moves (verify and expand):\n- The opening eight negations (no arising, no ceasing, no permanence, no annihilation, no coming, no going, no identity, no difference) framing dependent origination.\n- 24.18-19, the keystone: \"Whatever is dependently arisen is explained as emptiness... there is nothing that is not dependently arisen, therefore nothing that is not empty.\"\n- 24.8-10, the two truths: conventional and ultimate; without the conventional, the ultimate cannot be taught.\n- The deconstruction of motion (Ch 2): the goer, the going, and the gone.\n- 13.8, the emptiness of emptiness: \"those who take emptiness itself as a view are incurable.\" It is not a new absolute.\n- 25.19, \"there is not the slightest difference between samsara and nirvana.\"\n\nInterpretation splits for the sidebars: svabhava (\"inherent existence\" / \"intrinsic nature\" / \"essence\"), sunyata (\"emptiness\" / \"voidness,\" and why \"voidness\" misleads), prapanca (\"conceptual proliferation\" / \"fabrication\"). Compare Garfield against Siderits and Katsura (the analytic edition), Kenneth Inada, Frederick Streng, and a secular reading like Stephen Batchelor. Sanskrit source line + transliteration. Name the interpretive contest (Svatantrika vs Prasangika). Frame: this is the philosophical engine under the Heart Sutra's \"form is emptiness.\"\n\nWhen built and self-edited, add the homepage card, og:image, real sourced thumbnail (named). Verify 20px gutter at 375px. Commit and push with explicit paths."}]},"new-testament":{"title":"The New Testament, Side by Side","href":"new-testament.html","count":1,"prompts":[{"when":"2026-06-20T03:54","text":"You're building a post for my \"great books, made learn-from-able\" series. This one is the Christian Bible, centered on the New Testament. Approach A, curated keystones from the largest and most-scrutinized text in the series. Do this after the Hebrew Bible post and build on it.\n\nVOICE IS THE BAR. Read CANON.md first (especially \"What the first posts taught us\"), then VOICE.md and STYLE.md, study tao-te-ching.html and js/tao*.js. write-post skill, monotone test, plain warm spoken, concrete opener. Because this is the most-scrutinized post, source every claim and steelman the contested doctrines.\n\nClone the Tao architecture: new-testament.html, js/new-testament-data.js, js/new-testament-notes.js. deep-research skill, dossier in research/new-testament/. Source the best translations yourself via parallel sub-agents; do not ask me to fetch copies.\n\nThe spine (diagnosis and prescription): humanity is estranged from God by sin and cannot save itself; the repair is reconciliation by grace through the life, death, and resurrection of Jesus, lived out as love of God and neighbor.\n\nKeystones (verify and expand):\n- The Greatest Commandment, the self-summary (Matthew 22:37-40): \"Love God, and love your neighbor as yourself. On these two hang all the Law and the Prophets.\"\n- The Sermon on the Mount (Matthew 5-7): the Beatitudes, \"turn the other cheek,\" \"love your enemies,\" the Lord's Prayer, \"judge not.\" The ethical heart.\n- John 1:1, the Word (Logos): \"In the beginning was the Word, and the Word was God.\" Translation fork on Logos and the grammar.\n- John 3:16, the gospel in one verse.\n- The Passion and Resurrection, the load-bearing event, not just a saying: \"Father, forgive them,\" the empty tomb.\n- 1 Corinthians 13, Paul on love: \"If I have not love, I am a noisy gong.\"\n- Romans and Ephesians 2:8-9, grace: \"by grace you have been saved through faith, not by works.\" The Protestant keystone.\n- The Good Samaritan and the Prodigal Son (Luke 10, 15), the parables that carry the ethic.\n\nUntranslatables and forks to stack: Logos (Word / Reason), agape (love / charity, KJV \"charity\" vs modern \"love\" in 1 Cor 13), metanoia (repentance / change of mind), pistis (faith / trust), the Lord's Prayer wording (debts / trespasses / sins), and the famous Isaiah 7:14 \"virgin / young woman\" as quoted in Matthew. Greek source line + transliteration. The English-translation lineage is itself a dramatic story (Tyndale burned for it, then the KJV).\n\nTranslations (all fair game, name each): KJV and Tyndale (the cadence and its source), Douay-Rheims (Catholic), RSV/NRSV (scholarly), NIV and ESV (modern evangelical standards), N.T. Wright's Kingdom New Testament, and David Bentley Hart's deliberately strange literal New Testament (feature it, it defamiliarizes). Name the sectarian contest sharply: Catholic, Orthodox, and Protestant canons differ (the deuterocanon), and faith versus works splits Paul from James 2 (\"faith without works is dead\"). Focus this post on the NT and on how Christianity re-reads the Hebrew scriptures; do not re-treat shared Genesis and Exodus material covered in the Hebrew Bible post.\n\nWhen built and self-edited, add the homepage card, og:image, real sourced thumbnail (named). Verify 20px gutter at 375px. Commit and push with explicit paths."}]},"nietzsche":{"title":"Nietzsche and the Case Against Morality","href":"nietzsche.html","count":1,"prompts":[{"when":"2026-06-20T16:59","text":"You're building the Nietzsche post for my great-books series. Engine B. He is the series' designated dissenter, his job is to attack the convergence the other books share (humility, selflessness, pity as virtues). Let him.\n\nRULES: First read CANON.md (especially \"What the first posts taught us\" and \"The map\"), then VOICE.md and STYLE.md, study tao-te-ching.html with js/tao*.js. Follow the rules: voice is the bar (write-post plus monotone test, plain spoken, never formal, and Nietzsche is a great stylist, match his energy); open concrete; source the translations yourself via sub-agents, never ask me; 20px gutter at 375px; real sourced thumbnail (named); homepage card description ONE short hook line of about 15 words.\n\nSpine: the whole moral tradition is not eternal truth but a human invention with a history, and a suspect one, a \"slave revolt in morality\" by the weak to tame the strong; and \"God is dead,\" we have killed the foundation of our values and must either sink into nihilism or create new values ourselves.\n\nKeystones: \"God is dead\" and what it costs; master morality versus slave morality and ressentiment (the Genealogy, first essay); the will to power; the Ubermensch, the value-creator; eternal recurrence (would you live this exact life again, forever?); amor fati. Texts: Beyond Good and Evil and On the Genealogy of Morals for the argument, Thus Spoke Zarathustra for the famous lines.\n\nTranslations (all fair game, name each): Kaufmann (the standard), Hollingdale, Clark and Swensen.\n\nSpecial, do not skip: handle the Nazi misappropriation honestly, his sister edited and distorted him after his collapse; Nietzsche despised antisemitism and German nationalism. Let his attack on the rest of the series stand unanswered here, that is the whole point of including him.\n\nShip: card (ONE short hook line), og:image, real sourced thumbnail (named), 20px gutter at 375px, write-post self-edit, commit and push with explicit paths."}]},"plato":{"title":"Plato's Cave and the Death of Socrates","href":"plato.html","count":1,"prompts":[{"when":"2026-06-20T16:59","text":"You're building the Plato post for my great-books series. Engine B, the one-reading walk.\n\nRULES: First read CANON.md (especially \"What the first posts taught us\" and \"The map\"), then VOICE.md and STYLE.md, and study tao-te-ching.html with js/tao*.js. Follow the hard-won rules: voice is the bar (write-post skill plus the monotone read-aloud test, plain and spoken, never formal); open concrete with an everyday analogy; source the best editions yourself via sub-agents, never ask me; verify the 375px gutter is 20px; real sourced thumbnail (named); and keep the homepage card description to ONE short hook line of about 15 words (the cards so far are far too long).\n\nSpine: most people live chained in a cave, mistaking shadows for reality; the way out is philosophy, the examined life, turning toward what is truly real, even when the people still in the cave kill you for coming back to free them.\n\nKeystones: \"the unexamined life is not worth living\" (the Apology); the trial and death of Socrates (Apology, Crito, Phaedo, walked as the spine); the allegory of the cave (Republic, book 7); the theory of the Forms; the Socratic method of questioning everything.\n\nWalk it in one strong modern translation (Grube or Reeve, or Tredennick's \"The Last Days of Socrates\"), with stack sidebars on the famous lines. Translations all fair game (Jowett public domain, Grube, Reeve, Bloom for the Republic).\n\nSpecial: Socrates wrote nothing, so Plato is our only access, and the historical man may be half-invented; that tension belongs in the post. Concrete handle for the cave: a darkened movie theater, or a feed of shadows we take for the world.\n\nShip: card (ONE short hook line), og:image, real sourced thumbnail (named), 20px gutter at 375px, write-post self-edit, commit and push with explicit paths."}]},"quran":{"title":"The Quran, Side by Side","href":"quran.html","count":1,"prompts":[{"when":"2026-06-20T03:54","text":"You're building a post for my \"great books, made learn-from-able\" series. This one is the Quran. Approach A, curated keystones. This is the post that needs the most care; do it once the format is well proven.\n\nVOICE IS THE BAR. Read CANON.md first (especially \"What the first posts taught us\"), then VOICE.md and STYLE.md, study tao-te-ching.html and js/tao*.js. write-post skill, monotone test, plain warm spoken, concrete opener. Reverent and precise throughout.\n\nClone the Tao architecture: quran.html, js/quran-data.js, js/quran-notes.js. deep-research skill, dossier in research/quran/. Source the best translations yourself via parallel sub-agents; do not ask me to fetch copies.\n\nForeground the point that reframes the whole translation stack: Muslims hold the Arabic Quran to be the literal, inimitable word of God, so every translation is \"an interpretation of the meanings,\" not the Quran itself. That is the teaching, not a footnote. Feature the Arabic source line prominently and present it with dignity.\n\nThe spine (diagnosis and prescription): humanity forgets God, is ungrateful, and associates partners with the One (shirk); the way is submission (islam) to the one God (tawhid), gratitude, prayer, charity, justice, and mindfulness of the Day of Judgment.\n\nKeystones (verify and expand):\n- Al-Fatiha (Sura 1), the self-summary: the seven verses recited in every unit of every prayer, called the essence of the whole Quran. \"In the name of God, the Most Gracious, the Most Merciful... Guide us to the straight path.\"\n- Sura 112 (al-Ikhlas), pure oneness: \"Say: He is God, the One... there is none comparable to Him.\" Tradition counts it a third of the Quran.\n- Ayat al-Kursi (2:255), the Throne Verse, the most-recited single verse.\n- 2:256, \"There is no compulsion in religion.\"\n- The Light Verse (24:35), \"God is the Light of the heavens and the earth,\" the mystical keystone.\n- 16:90, \"God commands justice and good conduct.\"\n- Sura 19 (Maryam) and the shared prophets (Abraham, Moses, Jesus, Mary), revised from the biblical tradition.\n- A short late-Meccan sura like 81 (at-Takwir) for the vivid Day-of-Judgment voice.\n\nUntranslatables to stack: Allah (\"God\" vs left as \"Allah\"), islam (submission / surrender), rahman and rahim (the two mercy words, hard to tell apart in English), taqwa (God-consciousness / piety), and the opening of Al-Fatiha (\"Lord of the worlds / of all beings\"). Arabic source line + transliteration.\n\nTranslations (all fair game, name each): Pickthall, Yusuf Ali, A.J. Arberry (the literary one that echoes the Arabic rhythm), Sahih International, M.A.S. Abdel Haleem (clear modern), Muhammad Asad, George Sale (the first major English from Arabic). The Quran's text is essentially uniform worldwide (unlike the Bible's variants); the contest is in interpretation (tafsir) and the Sunni and Shia split on authority, not in the text. Note the non-chronological order (longest suras first). Give context rather than apologetics or hostile verse-mining.\n\nWhen built and self-edited, add the homepage card, og:image, real sourced thumbnail (named, and chosen with care, calligraphy or architecture rather than figural images). Verify 20px gutter at 375px. Commit and push with explicit paths."}]},"social-contract":{"title":"The Social Contract, Side by Side","href":"social-contract.html","count":1,"prompts":[{"when":"2026-06-20T16:59","text":"You're building the Social Contract post for my great-books series. Engine A idiom, but comparative: stack three thinkers against each other on one question, the way the Tao post stacks translations.\n\nRULES: First read CANON.md (especially \"What the first posts taught us\" and \"The map\"), then VOICE.md and STYLE.md, study tao-te-ching.html with js/tao*.js. Follow the rules: voice is the bar (write-post plus monotone test, plain spoken, never formal); open concrete with an everyday analogy; source the texts yourself via sub-agents, never ask me; 20px gutter at 375px; real sourced thumbnail (named); homepage card description ONE short hook line of about 15 words.\n\nSpine: why should anyone obey the state, and what makes power legitimate? Each thinker starts from a \"state of nature\" and builds a contract out of it.\n\nKeystones, stacked side by side: Hobbes, Leviathan (life with no state is \"solitary, poor, nasty, brutish, and short,\" so we hand near-absolute power to a sovereign for security); Locke, Second Treatise (we are born free with natural rights to life, liberty, and property, government rules only by consent and may be overthrown, the seed of the American founding); Rousseau, The Social Contract (\"man is born free, and everywhere he is in chains,\" the general will). Set the three against each other on the same three questions: what is the state of nature, what do we give up, and when may we revolt.\n\nEditions all fair game (public-domain translations of Rousseau; Hobbes and Locke in English). Concrete handle: a group stranded on an island, deciding what rules to write and what power to hand over.\n\nShip: card (ONE short hook line), og:image, real sourced thumbnail (named), 20px gutter at 375px, write-post self-edit, commit and push with explicit paths."}]},"zhuangzi":{"title":"The Zhuangzi, the Book That Laughs","href":"zhuangzi.html","count":1,"prompts":[{"when":"2026-06-18T12:31","text":"You're building a post for my \"great books, made learn-from-able\" series. This one is the Zhuangzi, the second great Taoist book after the Tao Te Ching, in Brook Ziporyn's translation. It uses Approach B, the One-Reading Walk.\n\nRead CANON.md first, then VOICE.md and STYLE.md, then study the reference build (tao-te-ching.html and js/tao-data.js, js/tao-notes.js, js/tao.js) so you can reuse the site shell and the breakdown idiom. Approach B is different from the Tao post: instead of stacking a chorus of translations for every line, you walk the text in Ziporyn's voice and unpack it, using the multi-translation stack only as occasional sidebars on the few famously compressed lines.\n\nBefore building, run the deep-research skill and drop a dossier in research/zhuangzi/.\n\nThe text: third century BCE, attributed to Zhuang Zhou. Wild, funny, paradoxical stories. The Inner Chapters (1-7) are the core; walk those, plus the best of the Outer and Miscellaneous chapters. Ziporyn (Hackett, 2009 Essential Writings and the 2020 complete) is the spine because his rendering of the playful voice is the achievement, so feature it.\n\nThe spine (diagnosis and prescription): we are imprisoned by fixed perspectives, rigid categories, the cult of usefulness, the fear of death, and the exhausting deliberate self; the way out is free and easy wandering, treating all perspectives as equal, spontaneity and flow, going along with transformation, and emptying the self.\n\nKeystone passages (these are both the famous and the load-bearing ones):\n- The opening: Kun the fish becoming Peng the giant bird, and the little quail who laughs at it. Scale and perspective. (Ch 1)\n- The useless tree and the giant gourd, \"the usefulness of the useless.\" (Ch 1, 4)\n- The butterfly dream. (end of Ch 2)\n- The equality of all perspectives, the \"axis of the Way.\" (Ch 2, qi wu lun)\n- Cook Ding carving the ox, the blade that never dulls. The flagship flow story. (Ch 3)\n- The fasting of the mind, and sitting in forgetfulness. (Ch 4, 6)\n- The happiness of the fish on the bridge over the Hao. (Ch 17)\n- Zhuangzi drumming on a pot at his wife's death, and his own death. Equanimity toward transformation.\n- Emperor Hundun (chaos) drilled with seven holes, and dying. (end of Ch 7)\n\nFor the hybrid sidebars, stack Ziporyn against Burton Watson, A.C. Graham, James Legge, Herbert Giles, Victor Mair, and Thomas Merton on the most compressed lines (the butterfly dream's last sentence, \"you're not a fish,\" Cook Ding's \"I go by the spirit\"). All sources fair game, name each.\n\nNote the authorship layering (Inner vs Outer vs Miscellaneous chapters) the way CANON.md says to name the contest. Play with the contrast to the Tao Te Ching: if the Tao is the gnomic manual, the Zhuangzi is the laughter.\n\nWhen built and self-edited against VOICE.md, add the homepage card and og:image, commit and push to main with explicit paths."}]},"best-photographs":{"title":"Photography's Greatest Hits","href":"archive/best-photographs/best-photographs.html","count":4,"prompts":[{"when":"2026-06-10T05:10","text":"I want you to build a blog post about the best photography in the world: the most\nbeautiful images ever made, displayed with the most beautiful presentation techniques\nthe web can do. This is a HUGE post, covering everything, everything! The main\nintention is for folks to really get to ENJOY the best photos the world has to offer,\nso the images are the stars and the page should feel like a world-class gallery built\nby someone who loves the craft.\n\nDeep research first, and cite sources, but don't double or triple down on\nverification, that is a waste of time. Research the photographers, the stories behind\nthe shots, the world records, the wild stuff, the perfection of the craft. Every image\ngets vibrant text: a specific image, a photographer, a camera, a darkroom or\npost-processing technique, whatever, as long as what we are sharing is cool,\ninteresting, funny, or crazy.\n\nTHE ONE HARD CONSTRAINT ON IMAGES: every photo must be public domain or Creative\nCommons (CC0 / CC-BY), license verified, credited under the image with photographer\nand source link. Download images into the repo at sensible sizes (cap around 1600px\nwide, compress hard, srcset for mobile), never hotlink. Wikimedia Commons, Library of\nCongress, NASA and ESA releases, Met and Rijksmuseum open access, Flickr Commons:\nthere is an ocean of stunning legal material. If an iconic photo is copyrighted (lots\nof 20th century work is), tell its story in text and illustrate the IDEA with a legal\nimage or your own diagram instead.\n\nA taste of the territory, go well beyond this:\n- The first photograph ever (Niepce, 1826), the first photo of a human, the\n  daguerreotype era and why those plates still look unreal\n- Muybridge's galloping horse, and ANIMATE it: the actual frames as a flipbook, the\n  series that proved horses fly and accidentally invented cinema\n- Dorothea Lange's Migrant Mother and the FSA archive, Lewis Hine's child-labor\n  photos that changed actual laws\n- Ansel Adams and the zone system, with an interactive before/after dodge-and-burn\n  comparison\n- Space photography: Earthrise, Pale Blue Dot, Hubble Deep Field, JWST (all NASA work\n  is public domain and jaw-dropping)\n- World records: most expensive photographs ever sold, the largest camera and largest\n  photograph ever made, gigapixel images you can pan around inside, the fastest camera\n  on earth (MIT femto-photography, light itself filmed in motion), the deepest image\n  of the universe\n- The genres at their peak: astro, macro, underwater, wildlife, street, portrait,\n  landscape, aerial\n- The craft itself: light, composition, the decisive moment, long exposure, large\n  format, film vs digital, what makes a great print\n- The cameras: Leica legends, 8x10 view cameras, the Hasselblads we left on the moon,\n  phone cameras eating the industry\n\nPresentation is half the post. Use the most beautiful display techniques you can\nbuild: full-bleed heroes, scrollytelling reveals, before/after sliders, deep-zoom pans\nacross huge scans, a flipbook player for Muybridge, lightboxes, film-strip horizontal\nscrollers, spec cards in monospace styled like contact-sheet notes, sections where the\npage drops to near-black so a single photo glows like a gallery wall. Animations\nwelcome anywhere they serve the photos. Respect prefers-reduced-motion.\n\nEasy, fun read, lots of wonder, captions can carry humor. Superscript citations with\na bibliography at the bottom.\n\nMultiple polish passes at the end: typography and rhythm, then mobile, then\nperformance (lazy-load everything below the fold, the page must scroll like silk with\ndozens of images on it), then a final read-through. God-tier UI/UX on both mobile\nand PC.\n\nDon't ask me any questions, take it to the finish and then return to me."},{"when":"2026-06-10T12:20","text":"So this post is awesome, but the history part makes it lame, especially opening with it. Maybe keep some, I mean definitely keep some (the horse movie is awesome), but let's focus on keeping the reader's attention and showing them things they've never seen."},{"when":"2026-06-10T13:30","text":"Please disregard that last message. Could you go back into this post and do some work for me? I really need a lot more images of modern photography, or at least photography from the past 30 years. Too much of this is focused on history; I want it to be eye candy for people to look at. Maybe even go into digital photography, PNG compression, and who knows what. I basically want to take out all of my context poison and give you the wheel to make a post that is hyper palatable, exciting, and that everyone wants to read. I'm open to completely changing this post."},{"when":"2026-06-10T14:22","text":"Can you choose a different image, one with color, for the furthest blog post? Also don't choose a space one. Then the caption underneath the title on the homepage needs to be smaller, and we need a different title for it."}]},"big-enough":{"title":"Big Enough","href":"big-enough.html","count":25,"prompts":[{"when":"2026-06-10T05:12","text":"Write a fun, easy-to-read blog post about maximizing muscle hypertrophy using no supplements besides creatine. Make the case that creatine is a genuine game-changer, essentially a \"hack,\" with benefits for both muscle and brain, and argue that everything else you need can come from diet and sun exposure. Keep the tone light and entertaining with plenty of visuals to hold attention.\nInclude the following:\nDeep, well-sourced research with cited references. Be thorough, but don't waste time double or triple-checking the same point.\nOptional subsections covering proper form for each exercise.\nA section on how this kind of exercise positively impacts the brain.\nA discussion of when hypertrophy becomes unhealthy for long-term health.\nA point about how few people truly min-maxed this until recently, so the long-term picture is still unknown.\nCoverage of how fast you can lose muscle versus gain it.\nA specific section on how some people are born with more muscle fibers than others, with great accompanying visuals.\nA major section on diminishing returns: the idea that the last 10% might cost 2x the effort and time, so the practical \"maximum\" isn't really the absolute maximum. Make BALANCE a central theme of the post.\nSections on stretching, cardio, tendons, diet, the best times of day to exercise, and exact training regimens.\nA take on caffeine: lots of people use it, but it frankly doesn't add much, and I personally never touch it.\nVisual and design requirements:\nLots of pictures and very complex, creative SVGs. Have fun with them.\nData visualizations and animated visualizations, plus any cool animations you can work in.\nGod-tier UI/UX optimized for both mobile and PC.\nDon't limit yourself strictly to my list, this is just acute guidance. Add breadth where it makes sense. Do multiple polish passes at the end. Don't ask me any questions, take it all the way to the finish, then return it to me."},{"when":"2026-06-10T12:18","text":"So on protein, we're talking about the last 10%, you know? Like 1.6 grams per pound... that's way past diminishing returns, is it not?"},{"when":"2026-06-10T12:19","text":"Oh never mind, I see it's kg not lbs. Can you make sure the whole article is imperial?"},{"when":"2026-06-10T12:41","text":"Okay, with the caffeine thing... is that true? Like someone who never drinks caffeine for years vs. someone who drinks it twice a day, the person who drinks caffeine seriously has an advantage? I doubt it, but you're responsible for the research. Also please ensure it's not just my narrative here and that we're being truthful in the whole piece. And you need to go find images for this article, get creative, no generic stock imagery."},{"when":"2026-06-10T13:26","text":"So for this post, I want the main theme to be that you don't have to be insane to get really really big. I really want to focus on that point of diminishing returns: how much protein do you really need to eat to get, I don't know, 70, 80, 90% of what that guy who's eating 1.5 g per pound is getting? And then where's that point on how much you work out, where's that point on how much you sleep, the whole nine yards. So basically a very natural, not-too-much way to get huge. Also, can you make sure that I didn't guide you too heavily and poison your context? I really want the truth and nothing but the truth based on real data."},{"when":"2026-06-10T14:01","text":"Wow, so this is all 100% accurate?"},{"when":"2026-06-10T14:10","text":"Is this live? I don't really see this highlighted anywhere in the beginning: \"Protein ~0.7 g/lb gets ~98%; the guy at 1.5 g/lb isn't getting 100% to your 90%, you're both at ~100%, he's just spending more. Volume: 10 sets ~85%, 15-20 ~90-95%. Effort: 1-2 reps short of failure ~95%. Frequency: 2x/week ~100%. Sleep: ~7h ~95%. Time: the only truly non-negotiable input.\""},{"when":"2026-06-10T14:11","text":"Come to think of it, I don't see all the images you added either. Didn't you add a bunch of images?"},{"when":"2026-06-10T14:14","text":"The chart at the top of the post, you can't even read the text in the red because there's no contrast. Also, we need to do some major overhauling, because everything just kind of mushes together. Yeah, you have a little bit of color, but a lot of the visuals are just green, followed up with more green and green. I feel like we need more vibrancy to punch the user and keep their attention. Maybe we could use more images."},{"when":"2026-06-10T14:24","text":"My big enough post needs a full overhaul. This should be a 30 min read, not 90."},{"when":"2026-06-10T17:47","text":"Can you update the thumbnail and remove all the text please? And the shading on the left?"},{"when":"2026-06-10T17:53","text":"I still am not seeing your changes on my website, it still says 90 min read."},{"when":"2026-06-10T20:23","text":"This post isn't centered at the top, need to look at that. Also I need a new thumbnail, don't want words on it... maybe use the main first image in the post, but only the very top of the image."},{"when":"2026-06-11T01:41","text":"A few things on the big enough post... you keep saying \"muscle\", like 10-20 sets per muscle, do you mean muscle group? Also you say 10-20 sets, that's a huge range; I think you need to either make it sharper, or explain why it's so wide. Lastly, where you list the specific workouts to do, please go more in depth, true to the article, getting 90% of the way to full 100% for a PPL 6 days a week. I'm interested whether this looks like 30 min or 1 hour in the gym, or 1.5 hours. Also please make all the sources at the bottom wayyy smaller."},{"when":"2026-06-11T02:01","text":"I must have misworded. I don't want to show the 100% version, I want to show the 90% version. Looks like you listed the 100% version?"},{"when":"2026-06-11T02:06","text":"I don't think you understand about the sources; they should be like fine print, okay? I should be able to see them all within my screen. I also want you to remove \"Educational, not medical advice. Talk to a doctor before starting creatine or a new program.\" at the bottom."},{"when":"2026-06-11T02:23","text":"I just really don't think we have proper balance among all these elements."},{"when":"2026-06-11T02:38","text":"This balance link is way too dark, in blue, you can't even read it."},{"when":"2026-06-11T02:46","text":"Make sure the reading column is 780px."},{"when":"2026-06-13T23:49","text":"All three of my last posts... I think the header is bad. I mean not the header, but all the components that open it up: the home button, the title, the words below the title, a paragraph below that, some visual, a description of it under that, then the body text. I don't mind any of my other posts, but these... the whole holistic view of it, I think it's too complicated, and it's just not beautiful, world-class balance like some of the best sites in the world."},{"when":"2026-06-14T00:33","text":"I think we should just kill that SVG graph at the top of the big enough post."},{"when":"2026-06-16T23:43","text":"On my big enough post, I don't want these three dots at the end. Also I don't want the scroll-down progress bar at the top on any of my posts, archived or not, when and only when on mobile."},{"when":"2026-06-20T00:49","text":"On my big enough post, this text is too small in this component, and this dark green component is just way too big, period. And this battery visualization is absolute garbage; can we just use an image of something online instead? Don't care about copyright. In the component titled \"More sets, more muscle, up to a point\" there's way too much text below that chart, let's remove as much as we can."},{"when":"2026-06-20T01:19","text":"All of these type components are too big... hey, I've pointed out a few specific components that need changing. What's my standard for these? Like, is my standard this size? If so, let's change it; if not, what other posts have it wrong? Also, I have a way of handling sources now with a drop-down box on my other posts, let's implement that here."},{"when":"2026-06-20T02:51","text":"In my big enough post, I like the thumbnail and the opening image, but I want to get rid of and replace the rest of the nude figure images."}]},"five-hundred-children":{"title":"Five Hundred Children, No Books","href":"archive/five-hundred-children/five-hundred-children.html","count":9,"prompts":[{"when":"2026-06-11T20:34","text":"You are writing a blog post in the tradition of comparative religion and the cognitive science of religion, two established academic fields that study religion as a human phenomenon. The audience is an intelligent, impatient reader, skeptics and believers alike. The piece is respectful, analytical, and agnostic on metaphysics. It takes no position on whether any religion is true. It is not an argument for or against belief, and it treats every tradition with care.\n\nTHE ONE QUESTION\nBuild the whole post around a single question: if you placed 500 children on an island with no books and returned in 200 years, would they have a religion?\nThe post makes the case for yes by laying out well-established facts in order, never by asserting it.\n\nTHE ARGUMENT THE POST LAYS OUT\nSeparated human groups do not rebuild the same beliefs. They tend to rebuild the same underlying architecture: a sense of an order or agents greater than the self, ritual, specialists who tend it, and rites for the dead. The specific doctrines (which god, which afterlife, which law) are where traditions genuinely differ. The structure recurs, the content varies. We share the skeleton and differ on the skin.\nThe argument is credible precisely because the overlap is narrow and structural, because the doctrines genuinely differ from one another, and because the piece concedes those differences openly rather than glossing them.\nThree independent lines of evidence point to the same structure, by three different routes:\n- Isolation: cultures in the Americas developed this architecture independently over thousands of years, evident when the two halves of humanity met in 1492.\n- Deletion: in the twentieth century, several states tried to suppress religion, and the same social niche tended to refill.\n- Subtraction: in the 1930s, a mutual-aid fellowship pared a Christian inheritance down under intense practical pressure and arrived at the same doctrine-free structure (Akron, Ohio).\n\nWHAT I WANT FROM YOU\nOutput the finished post in markdown, then five title options, then a short appendix listing anything you were unsure of. Do it in one response. If you genuinely cannot finish in one, stop at a clean section break and tell me exactly where you stopped, so I can say continue.\nIf you are unsure of a fact, soften the sentence or mark it inline as [verify], and collect every [verify] in the closing appendix. Do not state anything as settled that you cannot stand behind.\n\nLENGTH AND AUDIENCE\nBody: 1,950 to 2,250 words. Hard cap 2,400. Deep but quick to read. Assume high intelligence and no patience.\n\nNON-NEGOTIABLE RULES\n1. The post never uses the word soul. Leave room for the reader to reach that idea on their own.\n2. The post never claims the world's religions or scriptures say the same thing. It argues for convergence only on structure. The doctrines genuinely differ, and the post says so plainly. The argument is strong because the overlap is narrow, not wide.\n3. The fellowship is never presented as an independent witness or as proof that separated humans converge. It descends from Christianity. Its only role is to show which parts proved load-bearing under intense real-world pressure, the route to the structure by subtraction. Never write that Akron was the island.\n4. The convergent-evolution frame is naturalistic. It describes the human receiver (agency detection, theory of mind, the psychology of ritual) and says nothing about whether anything is received. Stay agnostic on metaphysics the whole way. At the end, do not let the frame masquerade as evidence for or against transcendence. Name the seam, do not hide it.\n\nVOICE AND CRAFT\nNo em dashes anywhere. Use commas, periods, parentheses, or the word to.\nNo side-by-side quote walls and no \"tradition A and tradition B both say X\" parallels. Matched phrases ignore context, translation, and base rates. Argue from structure and history instead.\nConcede early and often, but keep each concession to a confident sentence or two rather than mushy hedging. Every concession is credibility you can spend later.\nTreat cognitive science as a description of the human receiver, not a verdict on whether anything is being received.\n\nREADABILITY\nParagraphs are one to three sentences. Never four.\nMostly short sentences, with enough variation that the rhythm never flattens.\nGrade 7 sentence mechanics carrying graduate-level ideas. Plain words, hard thoughts.\nNo throat-clearing. Never \"in this post\" or \"let us explore.\"\nEvery section header is a hook that creates curiosity, not a label.\nEvery section ends on an open question or tension that pulls into the next one. Write each transition on purpose.\nAt most one bolded sentence per section, reserved for the load-bearing line.\nThe first two sentences must work on their own as a social media preview.\n\nIMAGES: 8 slots, one per beat, plus one deliberate non-image pause.\nInsert each image in exactly this format, right after the paragraph that gives it meaning:\n[IMAGE: what it shows | suggested source, prefer public domain or Wikimedia Commons | a one-line caption that adds information or tension | alt text]\nThe slots:\n1. Akron, 1935: the founders of the fellowship, or the house where it began.\n2. A remote island seen from the air, placed the moment the island question is posed.\n3. Two temples paired, one from the Americas, one from the Old World, matched in scale of awe.\n4. The Faravahar, the winged symbol of Zoroastrianism.\n5. A squid eye and a human eye side by side, or a simple convergent-evolution diagram.\n6. The deletion period: an embalmed leader's tomb with its queue, or a period anti-religious poster, or a cathedral repurposed as a museum.\n7. The fellowship's original six-point program in print, or a Serenity Prayer card.\n8. A closing island image, different from slot 2, quieter.\nThe prediction-game pause is NOT an image. It is a horizontal rule with generous white space, so the reader actually stops.\nNo caption begins with \"Photo of.\" Each caption earns its line.\n\nSTRUCTURE AND WORD BUDGETS\n1. Cold open, about 180 words. Akron, Ohio, 1935. Two struggling alcoholics build something with the shape of a faith: confession, amends, surrender, a core text, a congregation. Be honest at once: they were not a blank slate. They came out of the Oxford Group, an explicitly Christian movement. So this is distillation, not invention. What makes it rare is that we can watch it happen with the documents open, in living memory, under a demanding test: it kept only what actually worked for skeptics whose lives were at stake. Plant that test now, it is the engine. Then pose the island question in one plain sentence.\n2. The lay of the land, three sentences at most, folded into the top of the prediction game. Many people now claim no affiliation, yet most of them still believe in something. A shared holy book is mostly a feature of the Abrahamic traditions. Many traditions run on practice rather than text, and some have no text at all.\n3. The prediction game, about 330 words. The engine. Tell the reader plainly: if religion is a human universal, we can predict what the island children build before opening a single book. Ask them to write down three guesses. Then give them the deliberate pause (the horizontal rule) so they really do it. Now the reveal, structural: a strict reading supports convergence on an architecture, not a creed. The near-universals are an order or agents greater than the self, ritual, specialists who tend it, and rites for the dead. Then the move that earns trust: most readers guessed the specifics, a particular god, an afterlife, prayer, and those are exactly the parts real traditions differ on and that do not make the cut, alongside a savior, the concept of sin, and sacred law. The universal parts are the ones they took for granted. Then a second, sharper concession: even the inner idea people assume is universal, the self as the central obstacle and surrender as the cure, is not universal. It is a narrower, later theme, and we will meet who broke it. The skeleton is universal. The theology is local. (Load-bearing bold for this section: the universal parts of religion are the parts nobody preaches about.)\n4. The reveal that the experiment already ran, about 300 words. It ran at planetary scale. People in the Americas developed in isolation for more than ten thousand years, and when the two halves of humanity met in 1492, both had temples, priesthoods, ritual offering, rites for ancestors, and beliefs about an afterlife. The same broad architecture, built twice. Keep the honesty tight: acknowledge Norse contact in Newfoundland around 1000 AD, the debated case for Polynesian contact, and that the Americas were not religiously uniform. Then the deeper honesty in one clean sentence: neither side started from zero, both inherited the same human cognitive toolkit, so this is two branches elaborating a shared inheritance, convergence on structure, not proof from a blank slate.\n5. The dissenter, about 250 words. Introduce the one ancient tradition that broke the inner pattern. The Gathas of Zoroastrianism call for active struggle against the Lie rather than surrender, and name deceit, not pride, as the central failing. Let that stand as the strongest case that the inner theology never converged: the diagnoses genuinely differ tradition to tradition, which is why the skeleton is the real universal and the creed is not. Then the twist, handled honestly: this small tradition, on the order of a hundred thousand people today, plausibly shaped the heaven, hell, final judgment, adversary, and savior later found in Judaism, Christianity, and Islam. Flag it plainly: that influence is contested and the dating is unsettled. Then draw the structural point, do not drop it: if those features were borrowed down one lineage, then the Abrahamic agreement on them is not several independent witnesses, it is one. The dissenter doubles as a lesson in counting witnesses.\n6. The frame that replaces \"all religions are one,\" about 300 words. The right frame is convergent evolution. Eyes evolved independently dozens of times, and nobody calls a squid eye and a human eye the same eye. Religion is a niche humans keep refilling, not one truth wearing many costumes. Add the honest nuance, because it is your own situation: even independently evolved eyes share a deep genetic control gene, independent on the surface and common underneath, exactly as separated cultures share one human cognition. The frame also lets you keep the dark convergences honestly: ritual human offering arose on both sides of the ocean, which convergence predicts and which \"one beautiful shared truth\" cannot explain. Name the scholarly fight in one breath: perennialists such as Aldous Huxley and Huston Smith against critics such as Stephen Prothero, who argues the differing diagnoses matter more than the overlap. Then count witnesses in one short paragraph: related scriptures are not separate witnesses, the Bible, the Quran, the Book of Mormon, and the fellowship are one family tree, and the Sikh and Baha'i scriptures consciously synthesize earlier streams. The witnesses that count are the lineages with no shared ancestry that still converge: the Indian, Chinese, and American traditions set against the Near Eastern line.\n7. The deletion period, about 170 words. If 1492 is the isolation test, the twentieth century ran the deletion test. Several states tried to suppress religion by force: the Soviet Union, Albania which declared itself the first atheist state, China in the Cultural Revolution, the Khmer Rouge. What grew back was either old religion revived or new structures shaped like the thing they replaced: an embalmed leader kept as a relic and filed past in a queue, sacred texts and processions, heresy and confession, a single face raised into the empty seat. You can ban the gods and the niche refills, sometimes with the state in the god's chair. Convergence predicts this. A blank human future does not. (If you breach the word cap, this is the first beat to compress into two sentences inside section 6.)\n8. The receipt, about 250 words. Return to Akron, but do not call it an island, it was never isolated. Its 1938 word-of-mouth program had six points: complete deflation of the ego, reliance on a higher power, a moral inventory, confession, making amends, and working with others still suffering. Here is the honest reading. The fellowship did not reinvent the universal core, it inherited the inner part from its Christian parent. What it shows is the other road to the skeleton: not building up in isolation but paring down under pressure. The filter was that it had to work for skeptics whose lives were at stake, so it dropped the specific doctrine and kept a higher power left deliberately undefined, a practice, and a congregation. That is the doctrine-free skeleton again, reached by subtraction. The one famous later idea, acceptance, is the weakest of the supposed universals across the scriptures, and the fellowship added it afterward through the Serenity Prayer around 1941. Two men solving an urgent problem kept the load-bearing parts and shed the rest. Isolation built the skeleton in the Americas. Subtraction uncovered it in Akron.\n9. Ending, about 150 words. Show the reader that the thing they reached is the oldest line in the books: the law written on the heart, fitra, Buddha-nature, the inner light. Keep it honest: frame these as every tradition reporting that something seems pre-installed, not as agreement about what is installed, since fitra implies God and Buddha-nature implies none. Hold the fork open: pre-installed by human nature, or by something behind it, the post does not say and will not use its own frame to tip the scale. Close on the island children, and let the unsaid word arrive on its own.\n\nTITLES\nAfter the post, give five title options, each with a one-line subtitle. At least two titles under eight words. The best ones pose the island question or promise the twist without giving it away. No title uses the words soul or same.\n\nAPPENDIX\nEnd with a short list of every claim you marked [verify] or were not fully sure of. Include at minimum, if you touched them: the fellowship and Oxford Group dates and history; the six-point word-of-mouth program, its wording, count, and date; the Serenity Prayer timeline and the Niebuhr attribution; the isolation timeline of the Americas and the contact caveats; the temple, priesthood, offering, ancestor, and afterlife claims for Mesoamerica and the Andes; the claim that human sacrifice arose independently on both sides of the ocean; current figures for the unaffiliated and what they still believe; the count for the independent evolution of eyes and the shared-control-gene nuance; the scholarly status of Persian influence on Judaism and the dating of the Gathas; and Zoroastrian population numbers."},{"when":"2026-06-11T21:33","text":"So I haven't read this yet, but it seems to be pretty AA-heavy. The point was basically to say that every single religious text says the exact same thing, and the reason is that the exact same thing is in all of our hearts as humans; none of us are special or important or different, and we constantly come back to this point of seeking out this thing and writing religious texts. You could throw a million people on a million different islands, and given enough time they're going to come up with a religion, and it's going to have the exact same core principles, because it's something that's in all of us. We're not special. So don't redo the post right now, I'm just asking: is this covered in this post?"},{"when":"2026-06-11T21:38","text":"I don't understand the difference between the core principles and the content. Of course different people are going to have different cultures and different languages, but it's still the exact same thing, is it not? It's the exact same feeling that led to the exact same reason for writing down the exact same idea. I don't see why it's different just because it's a separate culture in a separate language."},{"when":"2026-06-11T22:12","text":"Does the post ever mention panpsychism or non-dualism?"},{"when":"2026-06-11T22:16","text":"Look at my 500 children post... how could this be a better post? What am I missing? I'm open to wide research on this one."},{"when":"2026-06-11T23:15","text":"\"It had confession, amends, surrender, a core text, and a congregation. The one part it refused to fix was which god you answered to.\" So here I don't understand: \"the one part it refused to fix was which god you answered to\"? Like, it refused to change that Jesus had to be the god? I'm so confused. Did you write the whole article with this unapproachable language? I need it to be hyper palatable. And \"Both came out of the Oxford Group\", what are you referencing here? I think you need to go back through the whole post with a proper voice please."},{"when":"2026-06-12T00:21","text":"\"Both men, a New York stockbroker named Bill Wilson and an Akron surgeon called Dr. Bob, had come up through the Oxford Group, a popular Christian movement.\" Is this true? I thought Ebby Thatcher came from the Oxford Group, shared the tenets with Bill, and then he took it from there. I didn't know both Bill and Bob actually started in the Oxford Group?"},{"when":"2026-06-12T00:30","text":"\"So it kept only the parts that worked. Hold onto that, because that pressure test is the engine of everything below.\" This wording is too complicated, and there's an em dash, I don't ever want that."},{"when":"2026-06-12T00:34","text":"I really am not sure we need to be stuck to this 500 children thing... I fear it takes away. Maybe I'm wrong, but no books? Children on an island, so they invent how to write? Do they write regular books first, then other stuff? It's just a lot of holes I feel like: \"Leave 500 children on an island with no books, come back in 200 years: would they have a religion? No books have ever landed here. That is the only condition the question needs.\""}]},"get-used-to-everything":{"title":"Do You Get Used to Everything?","href":"get-used-to-everything.html","count":3,"prompts":[{"when":"2026-06-20T11:17","text":"A blog post investigating and creating an idea based on fact: do you get used to everything? Does everything's effect on you die off over time, at least a little bit? So is the real question what you want to be used to? Also, I don't think I'm asking the right questions, I'm going completely outside my rails here. What is out there about this, and all its implications?"},{"when":"2026-06-20T16:25","text":"The post I made about how humans can get used to everything, does it also talk about eyeballing and muscle memory? A few examples: a chef who eyeballs his ingredients to perfection because he's done it so much; a racecar driver who instinctively makes the perfect lines on the track; the coffee roaster who can literally see the exact shade the beans should be, which would be impossible without all the practice. I'm not sure I know what I'm talking about; is there already a lot of research on humans figuring this kind of thing out? And if so, what is it, and do we touch on it in this post? If not, maybe we could include it and redo the whole post to make sure it's in there. That opens the door to a lot of other things too, so where else am I missing stuff on this post?"},{"when":"2026-06-20T16:40","text":"I take it back, I want it all in one post."}]},"longevity":{"title":"How Long Can You Live?","href":"how-long-can-you-live.html","count":9,"prompts":[{"when":"2026-06-10T14:07","text":"Please make a highly researched and cited blog post with custom visualizations about the longevity of human life. My understanding is that there's a cap at like 120 that no one can beat, and eating less is the real only hack. So do the research, tell me the truth, then ask me questions before we write it up. It needs to be hyper palatable."},{"when":"2026-06-10T20:11","text":"This chart doesn't make sense and doesn't look good."},{"when":"2026-06-10T20:18","text":"Also, I think all the graphs and charts need a new title font or something? Doesn't look good. Also the words at the bottom are just too much."},{"when":"2026-06-10T20:19","text":"Also, I'm confused: how can we say unfit is the worst, then immediately say smoking is the worst?"},{"when":"2026-06-10T20:20","text":"Lastly, the sources at the bottom need to be way smaller, they shouldn't take up all that room."},{"when":"2026-06-10T20:21","text":"Oh sorry, one more thing. Let's update the thumbnail please, to something like an actual image; go find a good one, not of an old person please, think outside the box."},{"when":"2026-06-11T01:47","text":"My how-long-can-you-live post is strangely not centered at the beginning. Also that top graph is trash, it needs major work. Also at the bottom there are buttons on the right that aren't standard for my site, please remove them; more posts and colophon."},{"when":"2026-06-11T02:10","text":"Get rid of \"Educational, not medical advice. Last reviewed June 2026.\", remove the three dots at the bottom, and for the love of everything, it's all out of balance: text in strange spots, home button not where it is on my other posts, the whole opening, the graph, and the text below it, it all just needs proper balance."},{"when":"2026-06-14T23:56","text":"Change this to one quick line: \"Out of a hundred newborns, how many are still alive at each age. A century ago the line sagged early, as disease and childhood took a heavy cut. Today it holds near the top, then bends down hard in the eighties and nineties. We squared off the curve; far more of us now reach old age, but look where both lines finish. We learned to fill the room under the ceiling, not to raise it.\""}]},"no-blood-test":{"title":"The Book With No Blood Test","href":"no-blood-test.html","count":1,"prompts":[{"when":"2026-06-20T16:25","text":"Let's do a blog post about basically everything in the DSM, but keep it concise and fact-oriented. I want to cover a lot, and let the reader possibly realize they may have something on the list. I want it to really tackle the issue of diseases you can prove, like ADHD and autism, along with many others. Talk about how some people actually screw themselves over by identifying with a disease they don't actually have. But it really needs to be factual, not political or heated. Where no one truly knows, we say that, and we talk about what that means: if we don't know, then how certain should you be, the person with the disease (or whatever it's called)? Let's also touch on addiction and where that lies. But let's keep it big; I want people to maybe find out they have something. If we have sections, each should also include a truly provable condition, how it's proven, and make sure it's a wild one, just for fun. This post will be kind of long even though it's hyper palatable and follows voice.md, so we'll need some nice pictures to keep it readable. Also, don't let me point you in the wrong direction here; what ideas do you have? I may not be in the right headspace, I'm just pointing in the general right direction."}]},"seven-habits":{"title":"The 7 Habits of Highly Effective People","href":"archive/seven-habits/seven-habits.html","count":3,"prompts":[{"when":"2026-06-18T02:06","text":"Make a blog post for The 7 Habits of Highly Effective People. It should be very concise and let anyone get all the basics and the most important parts, with a good understanding of it."},{"when":"2026-06-18T03:13","text":"Now we need a really nice image for the thumbnail please."},{"when":"2026-06-18T03:22","text":"No, like, go find an image; notice I have amazing images for my other posts."}]},"still-moving":{"title":"Still Moving","href":"still-moving.html","count":4,"prompts":[{"when":"2026-06-18T12:45","text":"I wrote a blog post on hypertrophy called Big Enough; now write one covering both stretching and cardio. Take it to completion and return when done."},{"when":"2026-06-20T02:38","text":"Don't want a colophon section, want to show sources with a drop-down like my other blog posts. I want to replace the last image and the first image with non-nude figures, don't care about copyright. These two visuals have overlaps: \"The curve that should run your week\" and \"Where the steps stop mattering\"."},{"when":"2026-06-20T02:58","text":"Did you follow my voice.md?"},{"when":"2026-06-20T03:08","text":"I don't like that really wide photo at the beginning, can you fix it and make a note so we don't make wide ones like that again?"}]},"sure-things":{"title":"Sure Things","href":"archive/sure-things/sure-things.html","count":8,"prompts":[{"when":"2026-06-09T18:07","text":"Can you write a very short blog post about how there is no proof for gravity? Like, we can run repeatable tests, but we don't understand it. That's true, right? Can you do massive research on this, and then quote that stuff?"},{"when":"2026-06-09T20:57","text":"Okay now... what else is like this? Like time, for instance. But what are all the things?"},{"when":"2026-06-09T21:04","text":"Great, now go all out, include all of this in that post. Please do research on it, but you don't need to double- and triple-check-validate."},{"when":"2026-06-09T21:50","text":"So I don't think the explanations on each are cool enough. We should really be proving something jaw-dropping, in a way that's hyper palatable even to readers who aren't scientists. Also, every SVG should be replaced with awesome images that you find, beautiful images. Also, are little blocks really the way to go here? Any way to display it better or categorize?"},{"when":"2026-06-09T22:44","text":"Can we get a nicer, top-notch thumbnail for this post please, an image? Maybe choose one we already used?"},{"when":"2026-06-09T23:25","text":"On my sure things post, on PC the header isn't centered; on mobile, the section headers seem to be cut off."},{"when":"2026-06-09T23:37","text":"Can you make the sure things post better? For instance the black hole: it opens with \"Einstein's equations predicted this ring of doomed light to the pixel.\" Like... that's a lot to unpack. \"Ring of doomed light to the pixel\", sheesh, that's baggage, that's not an easy read. Also, this was only possible because telescopes on opposite sides of the planet captured the same photon? Like, what? Is a photon that wide? Anyway, my point is we aren't wording it hyper palatable enough, and we aren't honing in on the coolest part for each."},{"when":"2026-06-09T23:52","text":"Make the #17 dragon the thumbnail please."}]},"tao-te-ching":{"title":"The Tao Te Ching, side by side","href":"tao-te-ching.html","count":3,"prompts":[{"when":"2026-06-18T02:06","text":"Make a blog post about the Tao Te Ching, specifically comparing many different translations, as many as possible for every chapter, then breaking apart what each one means."},{"when":"2026-06-18T03:08","text":"Yes go ahead, also get an awesome thumbnail, and push it live if you haven't already."},{"when":"2026-06-18T03:21","text":"Need an actual image for the thumbnail."}]},"the-number":{"title":"The Number","href":"archive/the-number/the-number.html","count":8,"prompts":[{"when":"2026-06-10T13:26","text":"I want you to write a blog post about how there is a path for you to live very comfortably without working. I want a lot of research done for this article, but we don't need any double or triple verification; I do want a lot of breadth and depth, and sourced. I want to talk about how there's a certain threshold, and all you have to do is reach that threshold and then you're good. You've got to do the research and tell me, but I think it's like $2.5 or $5 million saved up, and then you just live on passive income, a hundred or maybe $200,000 a year, which is a very comfortable standard of living in my opinion. So I want you to talk about what it's like before you have all this money: the assumption is you're just an American with debt, car debt, student debt, credit card debt, and either no degree or a mediocre degree, and then you take this path to basically have a well of money that never dries up. I really want to avoid getting too financial and boring people; the single most important part is that we don't bore people with too-big words. It's important to tell people about the crazy stuff, the loopholes all the really rich people use, but explain it in a way everyone understands, and that's kind of part of the plan. Then we want to talk about how many years it takes to get there. And we need to talk about how this isn't free, there are no free lunches, so you do have to be a good citizen and have value you can bring to a company. I want you to go really wide with this one. It needs to be concise, understandable and hyper palatable, but go really wide. Don't be stuck to just what I'm saying; decide what's most relevant. Please ask me some questions before you get started, whenever you think is best."},{"when":"2026-06-10T15:43","text":"My financial post needs to have images, and be more concise, it's too hard to read it all now. Also, that \"where is your line\" interactive thing should be more in depth, allowing more input and changes; I can't even bring my debt down low enough! Also you should be able to show averages on these charts to compare to myself."},{"when":"2026-06-10T16:15","text":"Need a nice real image for the thumbnail; think world-class thumbnail practices and find a good one."},{"when":"2026-06-10T16:20","text":"Looks like this chart kind of breaks. Also it's not super clear what we're saying; can we make it clear, like \"if you want 100k a year from passive income you must do X\"? But don't totally change this whole thing, just make sure we're getting this point across."},{"when":"2026-06-10T16:23","text":"Also maybe we need to change the size of it? Can't see the numbers move clearly, or the graph; maybe on PC we can use the whole screen."},{"when":"2026-06-10T16:35","text":"Where does it get this 80k number from? Shouldn't this be one of the things I choose?"},{"when":"2026-06-10T16:43","text":"So words are being placed incorrectly. Also, I feel like I should be able to set my target, and it should have a smart way of telling me what needs to change, you know? Like I want 150k a year. Also I think we should assume future inflation too, and include it in a very clever way that the user will understand."},{"when":"2026-06-10T17:26","text":"So the main area, the big section where you put in all the numbers and it tells you stuff: in this area you should choose when you want to retire, or the years to reach it, you should be able to set that. And there should also be a box showing realistically what that estimated number is actually going to be worth by the time you get to that year, because of inflation, and talk about what that really means: in actuality you need to save a lot more because of inflation. Or is it less? I don't know."}]},"third-thing":{"title":"The Third Thing","href":"archive/the-third-thing/the-third-thing.html","count":8,"prompts":[{"when":"2026-05-30T16:58","text":"I want you to write up a blog post about nature versus nurture. Research this as deep and wide as possible; be absolutely relentless on the amount of research, send as many parallel agents as you need and cut the project into as many phases as you need. Some of the best people in the world had the worst upbringings, and some of the worst people had some of the worst upbringings too. I think there's something to be said about how every person is given the opportunity, at some point, to start doing the right thing, and there has to come a time when it's actually you who was wrong, not the people who did things to you, because you carried it around too long. But there's got to be something to the nurture part, right? I think it's three-sided: nature, nurture, and then whether you do the uncomfortable things you know are right, rather than the things you want to do and are comfortable doing. I believe someone famous said happiness is doing what you know is right, pleasure is doing what you want. So there are three parts to this article: how you raise a person, the DNA they have, and then themselves, making thousands of decisions every day, simple ones like throwing a piece of trash and missing the garbage when no one's looking, do you go pick it up or not? Those accumulate: if you constantly do what's comfortable rather than what's right, your life is bad and you hurt people; if you do what's right even though it's uncomfortable, your life is good and you're kind. Now, I also want to parallel this with a full research study on service dogs, the profoundly well-trained ones. Compare different breeds, and compare within one breed, the worst version of that dog versus the best. Draw the parallels, but also draw out what's different, which should highlight the humanity in it. And lastly, include very high-resolution, eye-catching photos; it'll be too drab without pictures, and they need to intertwine perfectly with everything being said."},{"when":"2026-05-30T18:15","text":"For the main picture at the top and also the thumbnail, make it a real dog that's known, like a famous service dog, and include a fact about him or something."},{"when":"2026-05-30T18:25","text":"This post needs to be more concise in word count, probably a 60% reduction."},{"when":"2026-05-30T20:10","text":"This post is just not sucking me in. I'd like to go back to scratch, but first hear me out. I love the title, but I think we need to open with nature versus nurture: where did this concept begin, who is certain about it, who questions it, and how a service dog proves that nature versus nurture is correct. Then we go into humans, and how a human's life can be horrible if they constantly choose to be selfish and not do the right thing, and people who hurt, hurt others; and people who do the right thing, even when it's uncomfortable, are happy and don't hurt others. I want to approach the idea that some people never figure out that to get the most out of life they must put the most into it. There are folks with really bad genes and really bad upbringings, but oftentimes if they feel enough pain they turn their lives around and become some of the best people out there. And then, how important is how you raise your baby? There's this concept that if they don't feel enough pain they won't get it together, so there's a predicament: does it matter at all? Should you raise them harshly, or easily? And if you have bad genes, should you have kids? I want to bring together what the smartest people have said about these concepts into a nice piece, which I've decided we're calling \"the third thing.\" I want to hear all the different philosophies. Personally, I believe we're bound by a spiritual world, likely at the quantum level, that karma is real and we can't avoid it, and the opposite of karma is real too. I genuinely believe every person has the exact same chance; we're all offered a chance, and if we want it badly enough we can start living in a way where our life is good. But sometimes people die before they ever make that decision, and almost no one makes it unless they felt a lot of pain."},{"when":"2026-05-31T12:26","text":"Okay, now go back through, because I either want you to back everything with something real, like references to certain religions or research studies, or I don't want it in here! Like a real philosopher or something. I want this post to be a time for people to learn about stuff!"},{"when":"2026-05-31T14:22","text":"Please make that first dog picture fit like the rest of the pictures, with the correct width."},{"when":"2026-05-31T14:40","text":"That top dog still doesn't fit, it needs to fit the width of the text and the rest of the images. Also this page takes quite a while to load; I'd rather not lose any resolution, but maybe I don't need users to be able to zoom in on those photos, so maybe we can bring it down, maybe that's the reason it's slow."},{"when":"2026-05-31T16:42","text":"The way you're speaking, the tone you're using, it's just not drawing me in, and it's not hyper palatable or understandable by someone who doesn't read a bunch of books. I need you to redo the whole post. You can take a look at my All In post, I'm pretty much happy with that one except for section 6, so disregard that."}]}};
